1
00:00:14,014 --> 00:00:15,882
This is our special for the 2026 World Cup

2
00:00:15,949 --> 00:00:18,151
with soccer managers
Park Hang-seo and Choi Yong-soo.

3
00:00:18,218 --> 00:00:19,686
Manager Choi Yong-soo is also

4
00:00:19,753 --> 00:00:23,256
someone who went down
in the history of Korean soccer.

5
00:00:23,323 --> 00:00:28,028
<i>He was the top scorer in the preliminaries</i>
<i>of the 1998 France World Cup.</i>

6
00:00:28,094 --> 00:00:28,962
-Yes.
-Also,

7
00:00:29,029 --> 00:00:32,265
he was a key member
of the miraculous semifinals in 2002.

8
00:00:32,332 --> 00:00:33,566
PFFT

9
00:00:33,633 --> 00:00:34,868
He was a key member.

10
00:00:34,934 --> 00:00:37,237
There is a bit of controversy, but still.

11
00:00:37,303 --> 00:00:38,438
PLAYED A GRAND TOTAL OF 1 GAME

12
00:00:39,239 --> 00:00:42,008
Your presence on the field
isn't required to be a key member.

13
00:00:42,075 --> 00:00:44,844
-Yes, that's right.
-And he has won the K league

14
00:00:44,911 --> 00:00:46,579
with the same team

15
00:00:46,646 --> 00:00:48,715
<i>as a player, a coach, and a manager.</i>

16
00:00:48,782 --> 00:00:52,052
<i>He's the first and only one</i>
<i>to have this record.</i>

17
00:00:52,285 --> 00:00:53,153
RESPECT

18
00:00:53,219 --> 00:00:54,888
-He's a legend.
-Yes.

19
00:00:54,954 --> 00:00:55,955
That's all.

20
00:00:56,523 --> 00:00:59,426
Anything else? No? That's it?

21
00:00:59,492 --> 00:01:00,760
All right.

22
00:01:00,827 --> 00:01:02,862
-We made him look better.
-Listen to this guy.

23
00:01:02,929 --> 00:01:06,199
How have you been recently, Manager Choi?

24
00:01:06,266 --> 00:01:08,868
Ever since I was replaced
due to my poor track record,

25
00:01:09,469 --> 00:01:11,838
-I've been at home…
-You didn't have to say it!

26
00:01:11,905 --> 00:01:14,040
-You didn't have to!
-…and doing well.

27
00:01:14,107 --> 00:01:17,043
I spent many decades only playing soccer,

28
00:01:17,110 --> 00:01:19,979
so I've been enjoying my life very much
with my family.

29
00:01:20,046 --> 00:01:21,314
-At home.
-With your family.

30
00:01:21,381 --> 00:01:24,851
-I'm happy every single day.
-I see.

31
00:01:24,918 --> 00:01:28,054
But do you still ponder about
how to better the future of Korean soccer?

32
00:01:28,121 --> 00:01:30,657
To better the future of Korean soccer,

33
00:01:30,723 --> 00:01:32,058
I've been resting quietly.

34
00:01:32,392 --> 00:01:34,227
A STRATEGIC BREAK?

35
00:01:34,294 --> 00:01:35,862
-He's been resting quietly.
-Resting quietly.

36
00:01:35,929 --> 00:01:37,063
-I received a tip.
-Yes?

37
00:01:37,130 --> 00:01:39,866
It says you've been working
as a CEO lately. What's this about?

38
00:01:39,933 --> 00:01:42,035
-You hold a title as a CEO?
-Yes.

39
00:01:42,102 --> 00:01:43,670
So he's not taking a break?

40
00:01:43,736 --> 00:01:44,771
-Did you start a business?
-What?

41
00:01:44,838 --> 00:01:46,005
-I have…
-A business card?

42
00:01:46,072 --> 00:01:48,641
-…started an entertainment agency.
-What?

43
00:01:48,942 --> 00:01:50,543
THE CEO OF AN ENTERTAINMENT AGENCY?

44
00:01:50,610 --> 00:01:51,544
You knew, right?

45
00:01:51,611 --> 00:01:53,346
-What?
-What's the agency for?

46
00:01:53,413 --> 00:01:54,547
An entertainment agency?

47
00:01:54,614 --> 00:01:55,648
What's it called?

48
00:01:55,715 --> 00:01:56,716
It's called House.

49
00:01:56,783 --> 00:01:58,451
-House?
-House Entertainment?

50
00:01:58,518 --> 00:01:59,619
Do you work with soccer players?

51
00:01:59,686 --> 00:02:01,521
No, it's nothing like that.

52
00:02:01,588 --> 00:02:03,056
I do the laundry, the cleaning…

53
00:02:03,623 --> 00:02:05,358
So that house.

54
00:02:05,425 --> 00:02:07,627
I give rides to my children too.

55
00:02:07,694 --> 00:02:08,928
You're managing your family.

56
00:02:08,995 --> 00:02:11,164
-His family.
-Home management.

57
00:02:11,231 --> 00:02:13,666
And I've even been playing tennis lately.

58
00:02:13,733 --> 00:02:15,535
Whenever I see flies around my place,

59
00:02:15,602 --> 00:02:17,036
I take the tennis racket and…

60
00:02:17,103 --> 00:02:18,638
BUZZ

61
00:02:19,806 --> 00:02:21,407
The electric… That racket.

62
00:02:21,474 --> 00:02:23,776
-The electric fly swatter.
-Not the actual racket?

63
00:02:23,843 --> 00:02:26,713
-Buzz.
-After all, you were an athlete.

64
00:02:26,779 --> 00:02:28,548
Do you have lots of flies at home?

65
00:02:28,615 --> 00:02:31,451
You were catching flies
when the production crew visited you.

66
00:02:31,851 --> 00:02:32,919
A TRUE STORY

67
00:02:32,986 --> 00:02:34,521
Why do you have so many flies at home?

68
00:02:34,587 --> 00:02:36,856
Back in my day,
when people my age were young,

69
00:02:36,923 --> 00:02:39,359
-we didn't have much to play with.
-Yes.

70
00:02:39,425 --> 00:02:41,661
So catching flies
was a form of entertainment.

71
00:02:41,728 --> 00:02:44,597
Really? I've never heard anything like it.

72
00:02:44,664 --> 00:02:45,932
Kids who were a bit better off

73
00:02:45,999 --> 00:02:49,402
would tie up chopsticks with rubber bands
and catch flies with that.

74
00:02:49,469 --> 00:02:50,503
A rubber band gun.

75
00:02:50,570 --> 00:02:53,606
But I had to use a clear plastic bag.
Haven't you tried that?

76
00:02:53,673 --> 00:02:55,175
Once you catch a few flies,

77
00:02:55,241 --> 00:02:56,976
they'd fly with one another in there,

78
00:02:57,043 --> 00:02:58,011
and you can watch them.

79
00:02:59,078 --> 00:02:59,913
It was fun.

80
00:03:00,146 --> 00:03:01,681
DOWN THE MEMORY LANE WITH GRANDPA CHOI

81
00:03:01,748 --> 00:03:05,985
Hyun-suk, after you heard
Manager Choi was going to be here,

82
00:03:06,052 --> 00:03:08,054
you were surprised
after running an online search?

83
00:03:08,121 --> 00:03:09,856
-I was really surprised.
-Why?

84
00:03:09,923 --> 00:03:13,993
He was born in 1973.

85
00:03:14,060 --> 00:03:16,829
-He's a year younger than I am.
-That's right.

86
00:03:16,896 --> 00:03:18,731
He definitely doesn't look that age.

87
00:03:18,798 --> 00:03:21,134
-Anyone can see that he's not.
-In 1973?

88
00:03:21,201 --> 00:03:22,368
That's the legal birth date.

89
00:03:22,602 --> 00:03:23,870
PFFT HANG-SEO

90
00:03:23,937 --> 00:03:26,172
I was originally born in 1971,
in the Year of the Pig.

91
00:03:26,239 --> 00:03:27,473
-The Pig?
-I see.

92
00:03:27,540 --> 00:03:28,541
Wasn't it 1969?

93
00:03:29,475 --> 00:03:30,510
DARN YOU!

94
00:03:30,577 --> 00:03:32,979
-No, not 1969.
-Here's the thing.

95
00:03:33,046 --> 00:03:34,847
It's not like that now,
but in the days past,

96
00:03:34,914 --> 00:03:36,583
infant mortality rate was high.

97
00:03:36,649 --> 00:03:38,651
Parents would register their child's birth

98
00:03:38,718 --> 00:03:41,354
after their first birthday,
so some people were registered later.

99
00:03:41,421 --> 00:03:43,890
-Due to infectious diseases too.
-Yes, right.

100
00:03:43,957 --> 00:03:44,791
So I thought

101
00:03:44,857 --> 00:03:46,893
even though his legal birth year was 1973,

102
00:03:46,960 --> 00:03:48,061
he looked like a goner.

103
00:03:48,127 --> 00:03:50,196
-Wait, what?
-"A goner"?

104
00:03:50,263 --> 00:03:53,967
-Manager Park likes these jokes.
-He just laughed out loud.

105
00:03:54,033 --> 00:03:55,134
That was your biggest laughter.

106
00:03:55,201 --> 00:03:56,903
He laughed the loudest just now.

107
00:03:57,136 --> 00:03:59,038
HANG-HANG HANG-HANG

108
00:03:59,105 --> 00:04:01,908
-What did you think?
-He let the UV rays fall onto him

109
00:04:01,975 --> 00:04:04,444
to raise our national prestige.

110
00:04:04,510 --> 00:04:06,846
-It's a medal of valor against UV rays.
-Yes.

111
00:04:06,913 --> 00:04:09,515
I'm not the type
who cares a lot about my looks.

112
00:04:09,582 --> 00:04:10,750
There are guys

113
00:04:10,817 --> 00:04:13,486
who play with a thick layer
of sunscreen on their faces.

114
00:04:13,553 --> 00:04:15,788
I think it's an eyesore.

115
00:04:15,855 --> 00:04:17,890
-What about you?
-I didn't wear it.

116
00:04:17,957 --> 00:04:19,726
-You didn't?
-I didn't.

117
00:04:19,792 --> 00:04:21,060
JEEZ LOUISE!
= HOW DARE YOU LIE?

118
00:04:21,961 --> 00:04:23,363
-He'd wear…
-I didn't use sunscreen.

119
00:04:23,429 --> 00:04:25,231
You used to do this.

120
00:04:25,298 --> 00:04:26,599
He really did?

121
00:04:26,666 --> 00:04:29,135
-Manager Park would know.
-Back in our day,

122
00:04:29,202 --> 00:04:32,272
-no soccer players used sunscreen.
-Right.

123
00:04:32,338 --> 00:04:34,407
But Jung-hwan was a surprise to me

124
00:04:34,474 --> 00:04:36,276
back in 2002

125
00:04:36,342 --> 00:04:38,678
-with a pimple patch.
-The round ones.

126
00:04:38,745 --> 00:04:40,280
That was the first time I saw it.

127
00:04:40,346 --> 00:04:41,581
I asked, "What is that?"

128
00:04:41,648 --> 00:04:45,285
And he said he used it
to care for his skin.

129
00:04:45,351 --> 00:04:47,020
I was too dumbfounded
to tell him to peel it off.

130
00:04:48,087 --> 00:04:50,556
He used to spend lots of time
grooming himself.

131
00:04:50,623 --> 00:04:52,392
All I used was lotion.

132
00:04:52,458 --> 00:04:53,393
Toner and lotion.

133
00:04:53,459 --> 00:04:55,862
Don't even try to lie. Hang-seo.

134
00:04:55,928 --> 00:04:57,530
I agree with Choi Yong-soo's claim.

135
00:04:57,797 --> 00:04:58,998
MANAGER PARK!

136
00:04:59,065 --> 00:05:03,169
-He used to do lots of stuff.
-He'd carry around lots of cosmetics.

137
00:05:03,236 --> 00:05:07,006
You have to use different products
in the morning, day, and evening.

138
00:05:07,073 --> 00:05:10,076
Most people use two products
three times a day, right?

139
00:05:10,143 --> 00:05:13,313
But I used different ones each time,
so I had to carry six products.

140
00:05:13,379 --> 00:05:14,747
A TOTAL OF 6 PRODUCTS

141
00:05:14,814 --> 00:05:15,682
Six products?

142
00:05:15,748 --> 00:05:17,317
You used to groom yourself a lot.

143
00:05:17,383 --> 00:05:19,919
When I went to Italy,
that was what the players were doing.

144
00:05:19,986 --> 00:05:22,121
So you saw Italian players do that.

145
00:05:22,188 --> 00:05:24,290
When you saw them do that,
you should've thought,

146
00:05:24,357 --> 00:05:26,492
-That they're an eyesore?
-…"They're an eyesore."

147
00:05:26,559 --> 00:05:28,194
DROPPING HEAD

148
00:05:28,261 --> 00:05:30,663
In the end, those players
aren't even good at playing,

149
00:05:30,730 --> 00:05:32,432
but Jung-hwan was so good.

150
00:05:32,498 --> 00:05:34,434
That was why I couldn't say anything.

151
00:05:34,500 --> 00:05:35,335
SMILING

152
00:05:35,401 --> 00:05:36,936
Hang-seo was the type

153
00:05:37,003 --> 00:05:39,005
who hated seeing the players
that were concerned

154
00:05:39,072 --> 00:05:41,140
-about anything other than soccer.
-I see.

155
00:05:41,207 --> 00:05:42,942
But at the same time,

156
00:05:43,009 --> 00:05:45,178
he's very weak against strong players.

157
00:05:45,445 --> 00:05:47,146
HARD ON THE WEAK, BUT BABIES THE STRONG

158
00:05:47,213 --> 00:05:49,382
TARGET CHANGE

159
00:05:49,449 --> 00:05:50,950
I'm out of this conversation.

160
00:05:51,217 --> 00:05:53,619
AGAIN, ANOTHER FIERCE THREE-WAY BATTLE

161
00:05:53,686 --> 00:05:56,222
Even during the preliminary matches
for the 2002 World Cup,

162
00:05:56,289 --> 00:05:58,191
it seemed evident
that he'd do something big.

163
00:05:58,257 --> 00:06:00,226
So he adored Jung-hwan so much.

164
00:06:01,761 --> 00:06:03,229
-It's true.
-It's because…

165
00:06:03,296 --> 00:06:06,866
Well, he was an eyesore.

166
00:06:06,933 --> 00:06:09,001
So why didn't you berate him?

167
00:06:09,068 --> 00:06:10,670
"Jung-hwan, get it together."

168
00:06:10,737 --> 00:06:13,573
-I would've said it to Yong-soo.
-You would have.

169
00:06:13,639 --> 00:06:16,943
But he wasn't the type who talked a lot.
He's a bit of an introvert.

170
00:06:17,009 --> 00:06:18,911
So I had to beat around the bush.

171
00:06:18,978 --> 00:06:20,546
I did talk to him about it.

172
00:06:20,613 --> 00:06:22,882
We're here with Korea's best striker,

173
00:06:22,949 --> 00:06:26,719
Manager Choi Yong-soo,
the current CEO of House Entertainment.

174
00:06:26,786 --> 00:06:29,589
You have two children, right?

175
00:06:29,655 --> 00:06:31,357
My eldest kid is a senior in high school.

176
00:06:31,424 --> 00:06:33,292
-A senior?
-Already?

177
00:06:33,359 --> 00:06:36,763
My second kid is an aspiring soccer player
in his second year of middle school.

178
00:06:37,530 --> 00:06:39,031
-He's playing soccer?
-Yes.

179
00:06:39,098 --> 00:06:40,767
We received this tip too.

180
00:06:40,833 --> 00:06:44,804
Jung-hwan also has a son,

181
00:06:44,871 --> 00:06:47,473
and he was against him playing soccer.

182
00:06:47,540 --> 00:06:49,876
And it says you're the one
who knows the exact reason.

183
00:06:49,942 --> 00:06:50,877
What?

184
00:06:50,943 --> 00:06:52,478
As you also know, Hang-seo,

185
00:06:52,545 --> 00:06:55,948
he's an ambitious guy,
even though he doesn't show it.

186
00:06:56,015 --> 00:06:58,017
That's how he got here today.

187
00:06:58,084 --> 00:07:00,653
So the idea of Ri-hwan
surpassing him is something

188
00:07:00,720 --> 00:07:01,721
he just can't stand.

189
00:07:03,689 --> 00:07:06,659
His kid can't do better than him.

190
00:07:06,726 --> 00:07:08,761
I've met the kid, and he was

191
00:07:08,828 --> 00:07:10,129
quite good-looking.

192
00:07:11,097 --> 00:07:12,265
Bah, my man.

193
00:07:13,266 --> 00:07:14,100
You're that ambitious?

194
00:07:14,167 --> 00:07:17,637
Any parent would wish the best
for their children, not the other way.

195
00:07:17,703 --> 00:07:18,971
Good grief.

196
00:07:19,038 --> 00:07:21,607
-Wasn't that awful, Manager Park?
-Hey.

197
00:07:22,375 --> 00:07:23,209
Well,

198
00:07:23,276 --> 00:07:24,710
he may be right or wrong.

199
00:07:24,777 --> 00:07:26,813
VERY CONFLICT-AVOIDANT

200
00:07:26,879 --> 00:07:28,581
Come on!

201
00:07:28,648 --> 00:07:32,552
I don't think any parent would think that.

202
00:07:32,618 --> 00:07:35,054
Even so, how can you say
something like "bah" to your senior?

203
00:07:35,288 --> 00:07:36,889
GLARING, SCARED

204
00:07:36,956 --> 00:07:38,090
He finds hierarchy important.

205
00:07:38,157 --> 00:07:40,393
And you're just sitting there
even after he said that?

206
00:07:40,460 --> 00:07:42,862
-What he said was wrong!
-Right?

207
00:07:42,929 --> 00:07:44,931
Please discipline him.

208
00:07:44,997 --> 00:07:46,699
In that case, Manager Choi,

209
00:07:46,766 --> 00:07:50,002
do you not want your son
to surpass what you have done?

210
00:07:50,369 --> 00:07:52,071
PANIC IN THE EYES

211
00:07:52,371 --> 00:07:54,106
HARD TO SAY…

212
00:07:54,507 --> 00:07:57,677
Why are you applying your thoughts to me?

213
00:07:57,743 --> 00:07:59,879
But looking at him so far,

214
00:07:59,946 --> 00:08:02,515
I don't know, I don't think
he can be as good as I was.

215
00:08:03,850 --> 00:08:05,351
Isn't that what you're hoping for?

216
00:08:05,418 --> 00:08:06,686
I was born with talent,

217
00:08:06,752 --> 00:08:10,289
and on top of that,
I added my efforts and all.

218
00:08:10,356 --> 00:08:11,924
Well, you know,

219
00:08:11,991 --> 00:08:13,493
I agree that you tried hard.

220
00:08:13,559 --> 00:08:16,362
But I wouldn't say
you had a significant talent.

221
00:08:16,429 --> 00:08:18,998
Even the father didn't have…

222
00:08:19,065 --> 00:08:21,801
-He wasn't particularly talented either.
-He wasn't.

223
00:08:21,868 --> 00:08:22,935
You never know.

224
00:08:23,002 --> 00:08:24,437
I don't mean to compare,

225
00:08:24,504 --> 00:08:27,473
but Jung-hwan was already known
as a good player in college.

226
00:08:27,540 --> 00:08:29,909
He was a top player
even when he was in college.

227
00:08:29,976 --> 00:08:34,647
But Yong-soo was a late bloomer
who became a pro later and got better.

228
00:08:34,714 --> 00:08:37,450
Even when he was on the show
eight years ago,

229
00:08:37,517 --> 00:08:39,151
he briefly mentioned his son.

230
00:08:39,218 --> 00:08:42,355
He said he wanted him
to grow up like Messi.

231
00:08:42,421 --> 00:08:43,356
Not happening.

232
00:08:43,623 --> 00:08:46,359
THE DAD EAGLE IS FIRM ON THIS

233
00:08:46,425 --> 00:08:48,928
-Your son is probably watching too.
-You're right.

234
00:08:48,995 --> 00:08:50,997
He might return in eight years to say,

235
00:08:51,063 --> 00:08:53,766
"I didn't know
my son would make it this big."

236
00:08:53,833 --> 00:08:55,101
You might do that.

237
00:08:55,167 --> 00:08:56,702
He'll go, "What did I say?"

238
00:08:56,769 --> 00:09:00,172
-"I said my son would be like Messi!"
-Yes, you'll come back and say that.

239
00:09:00,239 --> 00:09:02,408
He got the DNA from his dad,

240
00:09:02,475 --> 00:09:04,644
so I'm sure he was born with the physique.

241
00:09:04,710 --> 00:09:06,846
Not too long ago, his son ended up

242
00:09:06,913 --> 00:09:10,950
watching our game against the US
during the 2002 World Cup.

243
00:09:11,017 --> 00:09:12,084
-Goodness.
-And then,

244
00:09:12,151 --> 00:09:14,287
-he said something to his dad.
-What?

245
00:09:14,353 --> 00:09:16,756
It's that moment with Lee Eul-yong.

246
00:09:16,822 --> 00:09:18,391
-Right?
-That tie-breaking chance.

247
00:09:18,457 --> 00:09:19,792
He's staring into the sky.

248
00:09:20,560 --> 00:09:24,864
Some say he's still looking for the ball
that flew over the crossbar.

249
00:09:24,931 --> 00:09:27,900
-That ball?
-That one, the biggest regret of his life.

250
00:09:27,967 --> 00:09:30,036
Some say someone got so mad
and popped the ball.

251
00:09:30,102 --> 00:09:31,470
I want to find that ball

252
00:09:31,537 --> 00:09:33,639
and rip it in half.

253
00:09:35,975 --> 00:09:37,410
SCRATCH…

254
00:09:37,476 --> 00:09:39,211
Back then, Eul-yong went,

255
00:09:39,278 --> 00:09:40,279
"Are you serious?"

256
00:09:40,880 --> 00:09:43,149
His assist was a 100 out of 100, though.

257
00:09:43,215 --> 00:09:45,618
-It was worth 100 points.
-It really was.

258
00:09:45,685 --> 00:09:48,454
-Perfect for a shot.
-It came in smoothly in the nick of time.

259
00:09:48,521 --> 00:09:51,290
"For you. On a silver platter."

260
00:09:51,357 --> 00:09:54,160
-All he had to do was take it.
-"Come and eat up this goal!"

261
00:09:54,226 --> 00:09:56,162
I think that was what put him off.

262
00:09:56,228 --> 00:09:58,798
-He was like, "I can have this?"
-"How can it be so good?"

263
00:09:58,864 --> 00:10:01,467
-"Can I have something this good?"
-"Should I pay?"

264
00:10:01,534 --> 00:10:04,737
-"I can't afford it, so I'll ruin it!"
-Just like that.

265
00:10:04,804 --> 00:10:05,972
I'LL RUIN YOU THIS TIME…

266
00:10:06,038 --> 00:10:08,240
Let's hear from him.
What did your son say?

267
00:10:08,307 --> 00:10:09,241
He asked

268
00:10:09,909 --> 00:10:13,045
why I played in that game,
when I couldn't play in anything else.

269
00:10:13,112 --> 00:10:16,115
He said, "You should've said
you were unwell and sit out."

270
00:10:16,182 --> 00:10:19,652
My physical condition couldn't keep up
with my determination.

271
00:10:19,719 --> 00:10:22,221
-I see.
-So I ended up shanking it.

272
00:10:22,288 --> 00:10:23,856
He was in great condition.

273
00:10:23,923 --> 00:10:24,991
WHAT DO YOU MEAN?

274
00:10:26,058 --> 00:10:27,159
-That day…
-His condition…

275
00:10:27,226 --> 00:10:29,795
The coach at the time says,
"He was in great condition."

276
00:10:29,862 --> 00:10:32,331
-That was why he subbed him in.
-Of course!

277
00:10:32,398 --> 00:10:35,635
Why would the manager sub in
a player who's in bad condition?

278
00:10:35,701 --> 00:10:36,836
He wouldn't.

279
00:10:36,902 --> 00:10:39,372
The manager had
the strategy all in his head,

280
00:10:39,438 --> 00:10:42,174
so he was subbed in
according to that scenario.

281
00:10:42,241 --> 00:10:43,909
The tactic was spot on.

282
00:10:43,976 --> 00:10:45,378
No.

283
00:10:45,444 --> 00:10:48,447
-In the end, it was a failure.
-Well, in the end, yes.

284
00:10:48,514 --> 00:10:51,250
-If only he had scored.
-You can play your strategy,

285
00:10:51,317 --> 00:10:53,919
but not everything goes according to plan.

286
00:10:53,986 --> 00:10:55,855
Even an ordinary person

287
00:10:55,921 --> 00:10:57,523
could've scored that goal.

288
00:10:57,590 --> 00:11:00,292
So making that ball go over the net

289
00:11:00,359 --> 00:11:01,894
means he wasn't worthy
of being on the team…

290
00:11:02,928 --> 00:11:03,863
WORN

291
00:11:03,929 --> 00:11:06,465
-That's…
-In my opinion…

292
00:11:06,532 --> 00:11:07,366
Hey, wait.

293
00:11:07,433 --> 00:11:11,070
Did you just say I wasn't worthy
of being on the national team?

294
00:11:12,038 --> 00:11:15,508
-This is bad. He's mad.
-I'm saying

295
00:11:15,574 --> 00:11:18,344
someone who plays like that
can't make it on the national team,

296
00:11:18,411 --> 00:11:21,981
so I'm trying to say
that what you did was just a mistake.

297
00:11:22,048 --> 00:11:23,916
After that,
you probably didn't get many chances.

298
00:11:26,085 --> 00:11:27,386
You were the first one

299
00:11:27,453 --> 00:11:30,990
who began to stop talking to me.

300
00:11:31,857 --> 00:11:32,958
-That's awful.
-I mean it.

301
00:11:33,259 --> 00:11:36,629
PARK STOPS TALKING TO CHOI
AFTER THAT BUTCHERED SHOT?

302
00:11:36,696 --> 00:11:39,398
I don't think
he talked to me for the next few days.

303
00:11:39,465 --> 00:11:42,201
-No, wait.
-Back then, the coaching staff

304
00:11:42,268 --> 00:11:44,503
did not include any former strikers.

305
00:11:44,570 --> 00:11:46,439
-Wait.
-So they didn't understand

306
00:11:46,505 --> 00:11:48,741
the instincts of strikers…

307
00:11:48,808 --> 00:11:50,943
Wait, am I trying too hard
to justify myself?

308
00:11:52,011 --> 00:11:54,146
-But then, everyone there was…
-Did you think so?

309
00:11:54,213 --> 00:11:57,416
…midfielders, defenders and goalies.

310
00:11:57,483 --> 00:11:58,851
Wasn't that so?

311
00:11:58,918 --> 00:12:02,321
-Why are you asking me?
-No coaching staff could understand.

312
00:12:02,388 --> 00:12:04,457
It must've been a lonely journey.

313
00:12:04,523 --> 00:12:08,027
He wasn't. He looked completely fine
even as he talked after that game.

314
00:12:13,365 --> 00:12:15,468
THE STRIKER OF TODAY'S SHOW

315
00:12:15,534 --> 00:12:18,337
"Choi Yong-soo, perfectly fine
even after the butchered shot."

316
00:12:18,404 --> 00:12:20,773
He must have a great personality.

317
00:12:20,840 --> 00:12:22,208
You should be grateful for me.

318
00:12:22,274 --> 00:12:23,109
Why?

319
00:12:23,175 --> 00:12:26,045
If I hadn't scored a tying goal,
you would've been in huge trouble.

320
00:12:26,112 --> 00:12:28,481
HE'S RIGHT
SO I GOT NOTHING TO SAY

321
00:12:28,547 --> 00:12:30,549
It was heartbreaking.

322
00:12:31,317 --> 00:12:33,285
Otherwise he could've been
at the front of the parade.

323
00:12:33,352 --> 00:12:34,820
All of Korea was thrilled.

324
00:12:34,887 --> 00:12:37,890
The tying goal made everyone happy
except for Manager Choi.

325
00:12:37,957 --> 00:12:39,191
Gosh.

326
00:12:39,258 --> 00:12:41,494
-But you were grateful for him, right?
-You should've been.

327
00:12:41,560 --> 00:12:45,064
-If you hadn't, we would've all gone down.
-If we didn't pass the group stage…

328
00:12:45,564 --> 00:12:46,632
Gosh…

329
00:12:46,932 --> 00:12:48,901
NO NEED TO EXPLAIN…

330
00:12:48,968 --> 00:12:51,170
He played an important role back then.

331
00:12:51,237 --> 00:12:52,872
THE HERO OF THE 2002 WORLD CUP

332
00:12:52,938 --> 00:12:55,441
Anyway, we hope to see great results
this year as well.

333
00:12:55,508 --> 00:12:56,742
All right, then.

334
00:12:56,809 --> 00:13:00,646
We're about to look through
Manager Choi Yong-soo's fridge.

335
00:13:00,713 --> 00:13:02,748
Eight years ago,

336
00:13:02,815 --> 00:13:05,284
your home fridge really surprised us.

337
00:13:05,351 --> 00:13:08,487
-We present Choi Yong-soo's fridge!
-Fridge!

338
00:13:10,790 --> 00:13:11,857
Long-legged octopus.

339
00:13:11,924 --> 00:13:13,559
Look at the size of these abalones.

340
00:13:13,626 --> 00:13:16,061
Black raspberries.
These are good for male vitality.

341
00:13:16,128 --> 00:13:18,464
Yes, I eat lots of great food.

342
00:13:18,531 --> 00:13:22,501
We could see
how he was loved dearly by his family.

343
00:13:22,568 --> 00:13:25,137
So how are things these days?

344
00:13:25,704 --> 00:13:27,373
Slowly, my position at home

345
00:13:27,439 --> 00:13:28,774
has been dropping.

346
00:13:28,841 --> 00:13:30,142
Wait, why?

347
00:13:30,209 --> 00:13:32,278
The contents of our fridge

348
00:13:32,344 --> 00:13:35,614
are centered around our children, not me.

349
00:13:35,681 --> 00:13:36,549
But still,

350
00:13:36,615 --> 00:13:41,320
as the CEO, I still have to maintain
the ingredients that I love.

351
00:13:41,387 --> 00:13:42,621
I see.

352
00:13:42,688 --> 00:13:45,724
We get to see his fridge again
after eight years.

353
00:13:45,791 --> 00:13:47,226
Please look forward to it.

354
00:13:47,293 --> 00:13:49,361
-We present his fridge!
-Fridge!

355
00:13:49,895 --> 00:13:51,831
-It's been eight years!
-Whoa.

356
00:13:51,897 --> 00:13:54,066
My gosh. It's neatly organized.

357
00:13:54,133 --> 00:13:56,435
-You still eat well at home.
-It's so organized.

358
00:13:56,502 --> 00:13:58,904
NEATLY ORGANIZED

359
00:13:58,971 --> 00:14:02,107
Did you organize everything
before you came to the show?

360
00:14:02,708 --> 00:14:06,111
I had to clean the fridge until 2:30 a.m.

361
00:14:06,445 --> 00:14:08,914
DOING OVERTIME
AT HOUSE ENTERTAINMENT AGENCY

362
00:14:08,981 --> 00:14:10,549
It was rough.

363
00:14:10,616 --> 00:14:11,684
Until 2:30 a.m.?

364
00:14:11,750 --> 00:14:16,188
I organized everything,
but the contents are what we actually eat.

365
00:14:16,255 --> 00:14:17,957
-Let's take a look at everything.
-All right.

366
00:14:18,023 --> 00:14:19,758
First, the top shelf.

367
00:14:19,825 --> 00:14:23,162
-Gosh. These already look delicious.
-Some side dishes.

368
00:14:23,229 --> 00:14:25,097
You have lots of Korean side dishes.

369
00:14:25,164 --> 00:14:26,465
Seasoned cucumbers

370
00:14:26,532 --> 00:14:28,234
and stir-fried anchovies.

371
00:14:28,300 --> 00:14:30,102
What's this? It looks delicious.

372
00:14:30,169 --> 00:14:32,004
IT ALREADY LOOKS APPETIZING

373
00:14:32,071 --> 00:14:33,038
-Octopus<i> jeotgal.</i>
<i>-Jeotgal.</i>

374
00:14:33,105 --> 00:14:34,306
-Octopus?
-Long-legged octopus?

375
00:14:34,373 --> 00:14:35,641
He loves <i>jeotgal</i>.

376
00:14:35,708 --> 00:14:37,610
-He does?
-He loves <i>jeotgal</i>.

377
00:14:37,676 --> 00:14:39,812
He always needs <i>jeotgal</i>
on top of his scoop of rice.

378
00:14:39,879 --> 00:14:42,715
-So you're a Korean cuisine kind of guy.
-I am.

379
00:14:42,781 --> 00:14:44,316
Is your wife a good cook?

380
00:14:44,383 --> 00:14:47,887
She can whip up
a mean <i>haemul-tang, </i>seafood stew.

381
00:14:48,654 --> 00:14:49,855
She probably only needs 12 minutes.

382
00:14:49,922 --> 00:14:51,757
-Twelve minutes?
-That's his wife.

383
00:14:51,824 --> 00:14:53,726
FINDS A CHANCE TO SHOW OFF HIS WIFE

384
00:14:54,460 --> 00:14:56,262
HEHE

385
00:14:56,328 --> 00:14:58,731
How many meals do you usually eat a day?

386
00:14:58,797 --> 00:15:00,332
When I don't have to see anyone,

387
00:15:00,399 --> 00:15:02,301
-about two meals a day.
-Two meals.

388
00:15:02,368 --> 00:15:04,470
When I go out on a business trip,

389
00:15:04,536 --> 00:15:06,138
I eat one meal, or not even that.

390
00:15:06,205 --> 00:15:09,642
-Why do you have to go on a business trip?
-Is there a need for that?

391
00:15:09,708 --> 00:15:11,477
-What business trip?
-He just said it.

392
00:15:11,543 --> 00:15:13,212
Where in the world do you go to?

393
00:15:13,279 --> 00:15:14,613
I'm busy with work.

394
00:15:15,114 --> 00:15:16,248
TO CATCH FLIES ELSEWHERE?

395
00:15:16,315 --> 00:15:17,249
To someone else's home.

396
00:15:17,316 --> 00:15:20,452
At times, I go out with my friends
to grab a drink and whatnot.

397
00:15:20,519 --> 00:15:23,622
That's just going out,
but you called it a business trip.

398
00:15:23,689 --> 00:15:25,958
Going out to meet friends
is a business trip to you, right?

399
00:15:26,025 --> 00:15:28,560
-I get it.
-We just call it going out.

400
00:15:28,627 --> 00:15:31,063
-But it's not an official business trip.
-He's just going out.

401
00:15:31,130 --> 00:15:32,965
It's not an official company.

402
00:15:33,299 --> 00:15:36,302
COME TO THINK OF IT, HE'S RIGHT

403
00:15:36,368 --> 00:15:38,470
What are these? Gummies?

404
00:15:38,537 --> 00:15:41,707
-They're probably for his kids.
-Those are for my kids.

405
00:15:41,774 --> 00:15:43,642
These look like Western ingredients.

406
00:15:43,709 --> 00:15:47,112
Those are for my kids too,
ingredients for pasta and whatnot.

407
00:15:47,179 --> 00:15:48,981
Who's the cheese for?

408
00:15:49,048 --> 00:15:51,650
My kids love it, and I like it too.

409
00:15:51,717 --> 00:15:53,686
-Do you like cheese?
-I do.

410
00:15:53,752 --> 00:15:57,523
I like to snack on it while watching TV.

411
00:15:57,589 --> 00:16:00,025
So yes, I do like cheese.

412
00:16:00,092 --> 00:16:01,860
Why are you staring at me like that?

413
00:16:01,927 --> 00:16:03,295
The chefs seem surprised to hear

414
00:16:03,362 --> 00:16:05,297
that someone with your looks
eats cheese as a snack.

415
00:16:05,364 --> 00:16:07,299
-Poong was really surprised just now.
-Yes.

416
00:16:07,366 --> 00:16:09,134
-You eat cheese while watching TV?
-Is this staged?

417
00:16:09,201 --> 00:16:10,869
Don't judge a book by its cover.

418
00:16:10,936 --> 00:16:12,638
I'm not staging anything.

419
00:16:12,705 --> 00:16:14,640
I heard you like to eat it as a bar snack.

420
00:16:14,707 --> 00:16:17,476
I rarely drink at home,

421
00:16:17,543 --> 00:16:19,712
but at times, I have some wine.

422
00:16:20,279 --> 00:16:22,881
-Huh?
-And I like to have cheese with it.

423
00:16:22,948 --> 00:16:26,018
What if you had to choose
between soju, <i>makgeolli</i>, and wine?

424
00:16:26,085 --> 00:16:27,853
-Answer truthfully.
-Truthfully.

425
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:31,056
-Soju, <i>makgeolli</i>, or wine. No staging.
-No staging. The real answer.

426
00:16:31,123 --> 00:16:34,026
-I prefer soju.
-He likes soju best.

427
00:16:34,093 --> 00:16:35,794
You definitely look like a soju guy.

428
00:16:36,228 --> 00:16:37,763
SOJU

429
00:16:37,830 --> 00:16:38,964
-Let's continue.
-What's this?

430
00:16:39,031 --> 00:16:41,500
-Watermelon.
-You've peeled and cut it.

431
00:16:41,567 --> 00:16:44,069
-Yes.
-You didn't leave it in whole.

432
00:16:44,136 --> 00:16:47,006
-That way, it's easier for me to eat.
-I see.

433
00:16:47,072 --> 00:16:49,575
Jung-hwan often told me

434
00:16:49,641 --> 00:16:52,544
that he had a tough time

435
00:16:52,611 --> 00:16:55,748
peeling and chopping fruit for you.

436
00:16:55,814 --> 00:16:58,150
Unlike how he looks,
he doesn't eat the peel.

437
00:16:58,584 --> 00:17:00,052
A PRECIOUS YOUNG GENTLEMAN

438
00:17:00,119 --> 00:17:02,187
He always needed it peeled.
Why won't he just eat it?

439
00:17:02,254 --> 00:17:04,056
Apples have more nutrition in their peels.

440
00:17:04,123 --> 00:17:05,691
So Jung-hwan used to do it for you.

441
00:17:05,758 --> 00:17:08,360
I used to pick out all the seeds too.

442
00:17:08,694 --> 00:17:11,163
THE REASON WHY HE IS
GOOD AT PEELING FRUITS…

443
00:17:11,230 --> 00:17:13,132
Take a note that he does not like peels.

444
00:17:13,198 --> 00:17:15,367
And vegetables. You got quite a few.

445
00:17:15,434 --> 00:17:17,169
Do you enjoy them? Asparagus.

446
00:17:17,236 --> 00:17:18,537
You like water parsley.

447
00:17:19,405 --> 00:17:20,572
How did you know?

448
00:17:20,839 --> 00:17:21,840
WHAT WILL YOU SAY NOW?

449
00:17:21,907 --> 00:17:23,342
What do you mean? Whenever we ate,

450
00:17:23,409 --> 00:17:24,877
you said, "Order water parsley."

451
00:17:24,943 --> 00:17:25,944
I'd go, "It's not in season."

452
00:17:26,011 --> 00:17:26,845
You'd say, "Order it."

453
00:17:27,146 --> 00:17:28,313
DID NOT BUDGE

454
00:17:28,380 --> 00:17:30,215
I'd go, "I'm telling you.
It's not in season."

455
00:17:30,282 --> 00:17:32,084
He'd say, "Just order it."

456
00:17:32,151 --> 00:17:34,353
How am I going to order it
when it's not in season?

457
00:17:34,420 --> 00:17:36,555
Water parsley… Yes.

458
00:17:36,622 --> 00:17:37,990
I remember that happening.

459
00:17:38,323 --> 00:17:40,259
A TOUCHING TRUE STORY

460
00:17:40,325 --> 00:17:42,795
So you like water parsley.
Any other vegetables? Lettuce?

461
00:17:42,861 --> 00:17:44,897
-He likes garlic.
-Garlic.

462
00:17:44,963 --> 00:17:46,999
-And chives.
-Chives.

463
00:17:47,066 --> 00:17:49,968
Chives. He says he likes chives.

464
00:17:50,035 --> 00:17:51,804
Some fish.

465
00:17:51,870 --> 00:17:53,772
We found them.

466
00:17:53,839 --> 00:17:55,307
-Here they are.
-What's that?

467
00:17:55,374 --> 00:17:57,676
-What's that?
-Brown croaker?

468
00:17:57,743 --> 00:18:00,846
-That's sea bass. Sea bass.
-What? Sea bass?

469
00:18:00,913 --> 00:18:04,383
Did your wife get this for you?

470
00:18:04,450 --> 00:18:05,651
We went and got it together.

471
00:18:05,717 --> 00:18:06,985
SHOPPED FOR GROCERIES TOGETHER

472
00:18:07,052 --> 00:18:09,388
-You went with her?
-Of course.

473
00:18:09,455 --> 00:18:10,289
Hey.

474
00:18:10,355 --> 00:18:11,890
Of course, I went with her.

475
00:18:11,957 --> 00:18:13,759
-It sounds suspicious.
-Not at all.

476
00:18:13,826 --> 00:18:15,561
Do you two hold hands and go together?

477
00:18:15,627 --> 00:18:17,296
After 20 years of marriage,

478
00:18:17,362 --> 00:18:22,000
I find it fun to shop for groceries
and cook food together.

479
00:18:22,067 --> 00:18:23,202
It's fun.

480
00:18:23,268 --> 00:18:27,072
-You couldn't do it while you played.
-He didn't.

481
00:18:27,139 --> 00:18:28,574
It's that he couldn't.

482
00:18:28,640 --> 00:18:30,542
So he loves to shop for groceries.

483
00:18:30,609 --> 00:18:32,177
I found lots of seafood here.

484
00:18:32,244 --> 00:18:35,447
-Manila clams.
-And some long-legged octopuses.

485
00:18:35,514 --> 00:18:36,982
You have eels too.

486
00:18:37,049 --> 00:18:38,717
That guy really loves eels.

487
00:18:39,418 --> 00:18:40,419
ANXIOUS

488
00:18:40,486 --> 00:18:41,720
-Eels?
-He loves eels.

489
00:18:41,787 --> 00:18:44,189
I once picked up
a piece of eel tail and ate it,

490
00:18:44,256 --> 00:18:45,924
then almost got beaten up badly.

491
00:18:45,991 --> 00:18:47,626
TWITCHING

492
00:18:47,693 --> 00:18:49,495
Let's say you ordered two eels.

493
00:18:49,561 --> 00:18:50,796
How would you eat the tails?

494
00:18:50,863 --> 00:18:54,366
-One each. One per person.
-Poong and Hyun-suk, you'd share, right?

495
00:18:54,433 --> 00:18:56,001
We couldn't eat any.

496
00:18:56,068 --> 00:18:58,137
-You can't eat the tail?
-No. He'd kill me.

497
00:18:58,203 --> 00:19:01,440
Is he exaggerating?

498
00:19:02,074 --> 00:19:03,542
No, it sounds about right.

499
00:19:03,942 --> 00:19:06,211
EVERYTHING HE SHARES IS A TRUE STORY

500
00:19:06,278 --> 00:19:08,313
He really doesn't lie.

501
00:19:08,380 --> 00:19:10,182
I found some dried seafood in the freezer.

502
00:19:10,249 --> 00:19:13,385
They're stored like this.
You have quite a lot.

503
00:19:13,452 --> 00:19:15,320
Now that the days are getting hotter,

504
00:19:15,387 --> 00:19:18,457
I like to pop a can of beer
and eat it with dried seafood.

505
00:19:18,524 --> 00:19:21,660
Since this guy is from Busan,
I saw him eat dried pollack all the time

506
00:19:21,727 --> 00:19:23,262
back when he was an athlete.

507
00:19:23,328 --> 00:19:25,397
-He always had one in his mouth.
-I did like them.

508
00:19:25,464 --> 00:19:26,965
You have to have something to chew on.

509
00:19:27,032 --> 00:19:29,334
Yes, otherwise, he'll chew someone out.

510
00:19:29,668 --> 00:19:30,736
HANG-HANG-HANG-HANG

511
00:19:30,802 --> 00:19:33,438
-Without it, he gets nervous.
-He needs to chew something.

512
00:19:33,505 --> 00:19:35,340
-He needs to chew on something.
-Yes, something.

513
00:19:35,407 --> 00:19:36,842
Without this,

514
00:19:36,909 --> 00:19:39,244
he feels nervous
and begins to chew someone out.

515
00:19:39,311 --> 00:19:40,913
He has no other way.

516
00:19:40,979 --> 00:19:42,614
There's no reason to chew anyone out.

517
00:19:42,681 --> 00:19:43,549
That's true. Yes.

518
00:19:43,615 --> 00:19:44,650
EYEBROW FLASH

519
00:19:44,716 --> 00:19:45,584
Jeez.

520
00:19:47,753 --> 00:19:49,888
He's so different
from when he looked through yours.

521
00:19:49,955 --> 00:19:50,956
And?

522
00:19:51,023 --> 00:19:53,525
-This isn't fair, man.
-What do you mean, fair?

523
00:19:53,592 --> 00:19:55,394
I'm reporting you to the KCSC.

524
00:19:55,460 --> 00:19:57,496
You'll report him to the KCSC?

525
00:19:57,563 --> 00:19:59,164
Look at this.

526
00:19:59,231 --> 00:20:02,734
-He does have lots of meat too.
-His children must eat these.

527
00:20:02,801 --> 00:20:05,737
-Those are all for the kids.
-These are what they like.

528
00:20:05,804 --> 00:20:07,673
Wait, you have duck?

529
00:20:07,739 --> 00:20:10,442
I do like duck. Duck meat.

530
00:20:10,509 --> 00:20:11,977
-He likes duck meat?
-He does.

531
00:20:12,044 --> 00:20:15,814
As the CEO of my entertainment agency,

532
00:20:15,881 --> 00:20:17,482
when I'm low on energy,

533
00:20:17,549 --> 00:20:19,284
I can't do any chores.

534
00:20:19,351 --> 00:20:21,520
-You need energy to do chores.
-That's why

535
00:20:21,587 --> 00:20:25,123
I need to eat good food to hold out.

536
00:20:25,691 --> 00:20:27,159
All right, then.

537
00:20:27,226 --> 00:20:29,461
That's all for Manager Choi's fridge!

538
00:20:31,597 --> 00:20:33,999
I wonder what he's looking to eat today.

539
00:20:34,066 --> 00:20:36,001
Show us his orders!

540
00:20:36,068 --> 00:20:37,569
Orders for CEO Choi Yong-soo.

541
00:20:37,636 --> 00:20:40,772
A Seafood Dish
to Make Busan Seagulls Soar.

542
00:20:40,839 --> 00:20:42,975
-A seafood dish.
-Tell us more.

543
00:20:43,041 --> 00:20:45,110
Busan is my hometown,

544
00:20:45,177 --> 00:20:47,446
and I came
with in-season seafood and fish.

545
00:20:47,512 --> 00:20:50,349
So I want to eat a hearty seafood dish

546
00:20:50,916 --> 00:20:53,719
that reminds me of my hometown.

547
00:20:53,785 --> 00:20:55,954
-I'm really excited for it.
-I see.

548
00:20:56,021 --> 00:20:59,491
-He's prepared to give his review too.
-Yes, ChoiPT.

549
00:20:59,958 --> 00:21:01,293
PREVIOUS EPISODE

550
00:21:01,360 --> 00:21:04,496
He said, "Do you know how to use ChoiPT?"
I said, "I don't know what that is."

551
00:21:04,563 --> 00:21:05,831
You mean AI?

552
00:21:05,897 --> 00:21:08,200
He was asking ChatGPT
to come up with stuff.

553
00:21:08,667 --> 00:21:10,302
HANG-SEO EXPOSED HIS TACTIC

554
00:21:10,369 --> 00:21:13,238
It's like seeing Son Heung-min
perform a curling shot.

555
00:21:13,305 --> 00:21:15,841
Did you just use
another one of your ChoiPT lines?

556
00:21:16,475 --> 00:21:17,743
Goodness. My mistake.

557
00:21:18,076 --> 00:21:19,544
WHAT WILL HE SAY FOR TODAY'S REVIEWS?

558
00:21:19,611 --> 00:21:20,979
He used another one of his lines.

559
00:21:21,046 --> 00:21:23,482
I'm sure he has amazing lines prepared.

560
00:21:23,548 --> 00:21:25,450
What's the next one?

561
00:21:26,184 --> 00:21:28,987
A Dish to Raise House Ent. CEO's Prestige.

562
00:21:29,054 --> 00:21:30,355
THAT TITLE IS JUST SO AMUSING

563
00:21:30,422 --> 00:21:31,423
-Okay.
-What's this?

564
00:21:31,490 --> 00:21:33,258
I find it a bit embarrassing.

565
00:21:33,325 --> 00:21:34,760
DEAD SERIOUS

566
00:21:34,826 --> 00:21:38,130
I'm slowly losing
my prestige as the breadwinner,

567
00:21:38,196 --> 00:21:40,866
and my fridge is the proof.

568
00:21:40,932 --> 00:21:42,401
Of course, I have my stuff,

569
00:21:42,467 --> 00:21:45,604
but most of the ingredients
are centered around my children.

570
00:21:46,538 --> 00:21:49,007
I'd like to ask you

571
00:21:49,074 --> 00:21:52,344
to build my prestige high up into the sky

572
00:21:53,145 --> 00:21:55,314
and make something that'll recharge me.

573
00:21:55,380 --> 00:21:57,082
Manager Choi, your family's motto is…

574
00:21:57,649 --> 00:21:58,517
Show off.

575
00:21:59,618 --> 00:22:01,386
-"Show off"?
-That's his family's motto.

576
00:22:01,453 --> 00:22:03,588
-His family motto is, "Show off"?
-It is.

577
00:22:03,655 --> 00:22:06,425
Please make a dish
that's worthy of his family motto.

578
00:22:06,491 --> 00:22:08,226
Four chefs who did not cook last episode.

579
00:22:08,293 --> 00:22:11,129
Choi Hyun-suk, Kim Poong,
Sam Kim, and Jung Ho-young.

580
00:22:11,196 --> 00:22:14,533
-Why don't we let the grandpa go first?
-Congratulations. We respect our elders.

581
00:22:14,599 --> 00:22:15,801
You're the CEO, right?

582
00:22:15,867 --> 00:22:18,370
I'll make something wonderful
that suits your title.

583
00:22:18,437 --> 00:22:20,639
Above all, my focus today

584
00:22:20,706 --> 00:22:22,641
is to make a dish

585
00:22:22,708 --> 00:22:26,411
that'll fit the review you prepared
via ChoiPT. I'm sure it'll be--

586
00:22:26,478 --> 00:22:27,646
It's not like that.

587
00:22:27,713 --> 00:22:28,814
OH, COME ON…

588
00:22:28,880 --> 00:22:30,649
I'm sure he prepared a wonderful review,

589
00:22:30,716 --> 00:22:33,452
so I'll make something that deserves it.

590
00:22:33,518 --> 00:22:37,322
A dish that deserves
the review he prepared.

591
00:22:37,389 --> 00:22:40,525
A Dish to Raise
House Ent. CEO's Prestige. Okay.

592
00:22:40,592 --> 00:22:42,594
Poong, I'll let you choose next.

593
00:22:42,661 --> 00:22:44,129
The dishes I make

594
00:22:44,196 --> 00:22:47,432
usually plummet someone's prestige
instead of raising it.

595
00:22:47,499 --> 00:22:50,235
-This order doesn't go with you.
-It really doesn't.

596
00:22:50,302 --> 00:22:51,870
So I have no choice but to choose

597
00:22:51,937 --> 00:22:53,772
A Seafood Dish
to Make Busan Seagulls Soar.

598
00:22:53,839 --> 00:22:55,207
-The seafood dish round.
-Seafood.

599
00:22:55,273 --> 00:22:58,009
Poong and Hyun-suk
are going their separate ways.

600
00:22:58,076 --> 00:23:00,645
Sam and Ho-young will
each have to take one.

601
00:23:00,712 --> 00:23:03,615
-We have the same number of stars.
-You do.

602
00:23:03,682 --> 00:23:06,218
So we should figure out who's better.

603
00:23:06,284 --> 00:23:07,786
-The second-place decider.
-Time to fight.

604
00:23:07,853 --> 00:23:09,821
-Busan Seagulls.
-Busan Seagulls.

605
00:23:09,888 --> 00:23:11,556
FOLLOWING POONG TO THE SEAFOOD DISH ROUND!

606
00:23:11,623 --> 00:23:13,859
The two with six stars will compete.

607
00:23:13,925 --> 00:23:15,527
-Oh, man.
-Chef Ho-young.

608
00:23:16,094 --> 00:23:17,329
I wanted the seafood round.

609
00:23:18,864 --> 00:23:20,699
You can raise his prestige
with a seafood dish.

610
00:23:20,766 --> 00:23:23,468
-Right. I'll do that.
-All right.

611
00:23:23,535 --> 00:23:25,871
Now, all matches have been decided.

612
00:23:25,937 --> 00:23:28,540
Let us now begin the round
for Manager Choi Yong-soo,

613
00:23:28,607 --> 00:23:32,277
-A Seafood Dish for Busan Seagulls!
-Seafood dish!

614
00:23:32,577 --> 00:23:35,414
STARTING RIGHT NOW

615
00:23:35,480 --> 00:23:39,785
<i>This is the first cook-off</i>
<i>played with Manager Choi's ingredients.</i>

616
00:23:39,851 --> 00:23:41,620
The one who turned over to darkness,

617
00:23:41,686 --> 00:23:45,290
the black swan of <i>Chef & My Fridge,</i>
Chef Sam Kim,

618
00:23:45,357 --> 00:23:49,294
versus the one who tried to run after
the chefs even before he learned to walk,

619
00:23:49,361 --> 00:23:52,030
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

620
00:23:52,097 --> 00:23:54,766
You two currently have
the same number of stars, six.

621
00:23:54,833 --> 00:23:57,536
The winner of this round
will solely be in second place.

622
00:23:57,602 --> 00:24:00,005
-Yes.
-What now?

623
00:24:00,071 --> 00:24:01,139
I'm sorry,

624
00:24:01,206 --> 00:24:03,275
but don't ask questions
when I'm hosting the show.

625
00:24:03,575 --> 00:24:04,910
FEELING SILLY

626
00:24:04,976 --> 00:24:07,546
He asked, "What now?"
I'm trying to run the show here.

627
00:24:07,612 --> 00:24:09,915
How am I supposed to answer that?

628
00:24:09,981 --> 00:24:11,516
It's been eight years since last time.

629
00:24:13,218 --> 00:24:16,288
Chef Sam has been raging this year.

630
00:24:16,354 --> 00:24:20,325
Last year, he ended the season
with only seven stars,

631
00:24:20,392 --> 00:24:22,861
so he's already close
to beating last year's record.

632
00:24:22,928 --> 00:24:26,465
Actually, Chef Sam
was the original Poongphobia patient.

633
00:24:26,531 --> 00:24:27,766
I will show my terror

634
00:24:27,833 --> 00:24:31,369
and make him relapse into Poongphobia.

635
00:24:31,436 --> 00:24:34,506
-So Sam was the one who was scared of you.
-Yes.

636
00:24:34,573 --> 00:24:37,342
It looks like
Sam is dying to win the star.

637
00:24:37,409 --> 00:24:39,578
He's not a guy who says stuff like this.

638
00:24:39,644 --> 00:24:41,847
He's ready to do a voice impression.

639
00:24:41,913 --> 00:24:43,949
-Chef Sam?
-Yes, it's Chef Sam.

640
00:24:44,015 --> 00:24:45,250
He's not like that.

641
00:24:45,317 --> 00:24:48,920
-He's dying to win a star.
-An impression of Manager Choi.

642
00:24:49,120 --> 00:24:50,856
THE FRIDGE OWNER LOOKS PLEASED

643
00:24:51,089 --> 00:24:52,691
EXCITED

644
00:24:52,757 --> 00:24:54,793
This honestly has
nothing to do with the star.

645
00:24:54,860 --> 00:24:57,963
I watched every episode
of your variety show, <i>Shooting Star.</i>

646
00:24:58,029 --> 00:25:00,198
-<i>Shooting Star.</i>
-I see.

647
00:25:00,265 --> 00:25:02,767
It was the first show
I watched from the beginning to the end.

648
00:25:02,834 --> 00:25:05,604
Shouldn't you be watching
<i>The Gentlemen's League?</i>

649
00:25:05,670 --> 00:25:08,073
He was really fun on that show,
so I became his fan.

650
00:25:08,139 --> 00:25:09,508
He won't even listen.

651
00:25:09,574 --> 00:25:12,010
Whenever the players
are devastated after a loss,

652
00:25:12,077 --> 00:25:13,712
there's something he always says.

653
00:25:13,979 --> 00:25:15,313
WHAT WAS IT?

654
00:25:15,380 --> 00:25:18,450
He always says, "An open-minded leader."

655
00:25:18,517 --> 00:25:19,851
-"An open-minded leader."
-"An open-minded leader."

656
00:25:20,051 --> 00:25:21,319
PFFT

657
00:25:21,586 --> 00:25:22,854
PARK PFFT-SEO

658
00:25:23,388 --> 00:25:24,723
HANG-SEO?

659
00:25:24,789 --> 00:25:26,658
He was in the middle
of saying something good.

660
00:25:26,725 --> 00:25:27,993
He just cracked up.

661
00:25:28,260 --> 00:25:30,028
THINKING

662
00:25:30,095 --> 00:25:31,730
I thought I had already lost

663
00:25:31,796 --> 00:25:33,632
most of my regional accent.

664
00:25:33,698 --> 00:25:35,534
-Sorry?
-He thought he had lost it already.

665
00:25:35,600 --> 00:25:39,271
Can you say, "I'm glad to be
on <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>" in a neutral accent?

666
00:25:39,337 --> 00:25:43,475
I got to return to <i>Chef & My Fridge</i>
with Hang-seo today,

667
00:25:43,542 --> 00:25:45,010
so it feels…

668
00:25:45,076 --> 00:25:46,511
great.

669
00:25:46,778 --> 00:25:48,113
HIS BUSAN DIALECT IS GREAT

670
00:25:48,947 --> 00:25:51,016
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S INGREDIENTS:
EEL, ABALONE, FISH CAKE, GLASS NOODLES

671
00:25:51,082 --> 00:25:53,118
WATER PARSLEY, CHIVE, PERILLA LEAF,
NAPA CABBAGE, RADISH, AND MORE

672
00:25:53,184 --> 00:25:55,854
The name of my dish

673
00:25:55,921 --> 00:25:58,590
is Shooting for Wacky <i>Jangeo-tang.</i>

674
00:25:58,657 --> 00:26:00,792
-He's making spicy eel stew.
-Shooting for Wacky <i>Jangeo-tang.</i>

675
00:26:00,859 --> 00:26:02,661
I'll make <i>jangeo-tang</i>, spicy eel stew,

676
00:26:02,727 --> 00:26:04,195
and Busan's specialty,

677
00:26:04,262 --> 00:26:05,797
<i>bibim-dangmyeon</i>, spicy glass noodles.

678
00:26:05,864 --> 00:26:08,466
I'm sure everyone from Busan
would love <i>bibim-dangmyeon</i>.

679
00:26:09,167 --> 00:26:10,669
You mean <i>milmyeon</i>, wheat <i>naengmyeon?</i>

680
00:26:10,735 --> 00:26:12,504
Of course, <i>milmyeon</i> is the best.

681
00:26:12,571 --> 00:26:16,041
There's no other specialty dish of Busan
that's better than <i>milmyeon</i>.

682
00:26:16,107 --> 00:26:18,176
But <i>bibim-dangmyeon</i> comes

683
00:26:18,243 --> 00:26:19,744
with the memories of Busan

684
00:26:19,811 --> 00:26:21,746
as well as all its joys and sorrows.

685
00:26:22,113 --> 00:26:23,582
GOING DOWN THE MEMORY LANE?

686
00:26:23,648 --> 00:26:26,117
<i>-Bibim-dangmyeon?</i>
<i>-</i>Yes, <i>bibim-dangmyeon.</i>

687
00:26:26,184 --> 00:26:28,219
-I've never heard of it.
-Never?

688
00:26:28,520 --> 00:26:29,921
IT'S AN EMERGENCY

689
00:26:29,988 --> 00:26:31,556
Anyway, it's a special dish

690
00:26:31,623 --> 00:26:33,658
made a bit classier with abalones.

691
00:26:33,725 --> 00:26:35,961
Let me whip up
something delicious for you.

692
00:26:36,027 --> 00:26:38,063
Is <i>jangeo-tang</i>
also another specialty of Busan?

693
00:26:38,129 --> 00:26:39,598
Isn't that something

694
00:26:39,664 --> 00:26:41,099
you can easily find anywhere?

695
00:26:42,801 --> 00:26:44,769
I always had <i>jangeo-tang</i>
whenever I visited Busan.

696
00:26:45,070 --> 00:26:46,504
DYING FROM LAUGHTER

697
00:26:46,571 --> 00:26:48,306
Busan has amazing grilled sea eels,

698
00:26:48,373 --> 00:26:50,709
-as well as <i>gukbap </i>and <i>milmyeon</i>.
-Yes, <i>milmyeon</i>.

699
00:26:50,775 --> 00:26:52,410
Busan is famous for <i>jangeo-tang.</i>

700
00:26:52,477 --> 00:26:55,547
-Manager Park says it's famous there.
-It's made

701
00:26:55,614 --> 00:26:59,651
with sea eels, not freshwater eels.
You often eat it there, don't you?

702
00:26:59,718 --> 00:27:02,320
-I do like <i>jangeo-tang.</i>
-Yes, okay.

703
00:27:02,387 --> 00:27:03,989
-I do, but…
-In that case,

704
00:27:04,055 --> 00:27:06,891
let me create
a new memory of Busan for you today.

705
00:27:08,627 --> 00:27:10,662
CHEF SAM'S INGREDIENTS:
SEA BASS, MANILA CLAM, MARSH CLAM, SQUID

706
00:27:10,729 --> 00:27:12,797
SHRIMP, RADISH, DUREUP, SCALLION,
STICKY RICE POWDER, MSG

707
00:27:12,864 --> 00:27:16,167
What about you, Chef Sam?
What are you making today?

708
00:27:16,234 --> 00:27:18,036
The name of my dish is

709
00:27:18,603 --> 00:27:20,572
Want to Stroll Around Dongnae With Me?

710
00:27:20,639 --> 00:27:22,674
-Around Dongnae?
-Dongnae?

711
00:27:22,741 --> 00:27:25,143
-Want to Stroll Around Dongnae With Me?
-With you?

712
00:27:25,210 --> 00:27:28,346
He's originally from Dongnae.

713
00:27:28,413 --> 00:27:30,782
-And it's famous for scallion <i>jeon</i>.
-Scallion <i>jeon</i>.

714
00:27:30,849 --> 00:27:32,617
-Dongnae scallion <i>jeon</i>.
-So I'll make that.

715
00:27:32,684 --> 00:27:36,821
Also, the area catches lots of sea bass
near Nakdonggang River in summer,

716
00:27:36,888 --> 00:27:38,657
so I'll grill some sea bass

717
00:27:38,723 --> 00:27:41,326
and use it to make <i>jiri</i>,
a type of fish soup.

718
00:27:41,393 --> 00:27:43,695
-Clear soup.
-Lastly, I'll make hot pot rice

719
00:27:43,762 --> 00:27:47,198
-with <i>dureup</i> on top.
-<i>Dureup</i> hot pot rice.

720
00:27:47,265 --> 00:27:49,100
-I'll make that too.
-Okay.

721
00:27:49,167 --> 00:27:50,669
-In 15 minutes?
-You like scallion <i>jeon</i>.

722
00:27:50,735 --> 00:27:52,404
I do.

723
00:27:52,470 --> 00:27:53,905
You like that and <i>dureup</i>.

724
00:27:53,972 --> 00:27:55,940
Isn't it past its season?

725
00:27:56,007 --> 00:27:58,309
It's an emergency. It's not in season.

726
00:27:58,376 --> 00:28:00,512
You eat water parsley
regardless of the season,

727
00:28:00,578 --> 00:28:02,514
but not <i>dureup?</i>

728
00:28:02,781 --> 00:28:04,149
HITS HOME

729
00:28:04,215 --> 00:28:06,317
I prepared water parsley!

730
00:28:06,384 --> 00:28:08,687
I will throw them into <i>bibim-dangmyeon</i>

731
00:28:08,753 --> 00:28:09,988
and also into <i>jangeo-tang!</i>

732
00:28:10,288 --> 00:28:12,924
WHICH ONE WILL CAPTURE
YONG-SOO'S APPETITE FOR BUSAN?

733
00:28:12,991 --> 00:28:14,025
All right.

734
00:28:14,092 --> 00:28:17,829
Let us begin this cook-off.

735
00:28:18,596 --> 00:28:22,267
He's about to score one last goal
and seal Sam's Poongphobia,

736
00:28:22,333 --> 00:28:24,335
Webtoon Artist Kim Poong.

737
00:28:24,402 --> 00:28:28,707
But he's here to gnaw and pop
Poong's soccer ball with his canine,

738
00:28:28,773 --> 00:28:31,309
Chef Sam Kim.

739
00:28:31,376 --> 00:28:35,246
Which one of them will become
the sole second place of the show?

740
00:28:35,313 --> 00:28:38,583
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

741
00:28:39,551 --> 00:28:42,220
HEY THERE, BUSAN!

742
00:28:42,287 --> 00:28:45,056
They're making seafood dishes
for Manager Choi Yong-soo.

743
00:28:45,323 --> 00:28:46,825
CHOP GREEN ONION INTO HUGE PIECES

744
00:28:47,092 --> 00:28:48,059
AND DROP INTO A POT!

745
00:28:48,293 --> 00:28:49,561
SEAFOODS TO BRING BUSAN HERE!

746
00:28:49,627 --> 00:28:50,462
Is that sea bass?

747
00:28:50,528 --> 00:28:52,731
And Manila clams for a refreshing flavor.

748
00:28:53,364 --> 00:28:54,432
And marsh clams.

749
00:28:54,499 --> 00:28:55,366
GARLIC

750
00:28:55,567 --> 00:28:56,401
RADISH, GREEN CHILI PEPPER

751
00:28:56,468 --> 00:28:58,403
He adds radish to freshen the flavor.

752
00:28:58,470 --> 00:29:01,306
Please make your dishes
taste strongly of Busan.

753
00:29:01,372 --> 00:29:02,941
That sea bass looks plump.

754
00:29:03,007 --> 00:29:05,744
-<i>Jiri</i>.
-He's going to make clear sea bass soup.

755
00:29:05,810 --> 00:29:08,413
I just received a tip as we speak.

756
00:29:08,480 --> 00:29:10,348
In his process of making that broth,

757
00:29:10,415 --> 00:29:11,950
he secretly added…

758
00:29:12,016 --> 00:29:13,551
…he secretly added

759
00:29:13,618 --> 00:29:16,755
some MSG.

760
00:29:16,821 --> 00:29:17,756
What?

761
00:29:17,822 --> 00:29:19,557
-Really?
-MSG?

762
00:29:19,624 --> 00:29:20,592
I did.

763
00:29:24,662 --> 00:29:25,830
SPRINKLE

764
00:29:26,064 --> 00:29:26,998
ADDS IN A FLASH

765
00:29:27,065 --> 00:29:28,299
You really are dying to win.

766
00:29:28,366 --> 00:29:30,034
You're taking things way too far.

767
00:29:30,335 --> 00:29:31,836
YOU GUYS ALSO BICKER A LOT HERE

768
00:29:31,903 --> 00:29:34,272
-You're not just using the veggies?
-It adds flavor to clear soups.

769
00:29:34,339 --> 00:29:37,175
-Really?
-He used to use only pure veggie broth.

770
00:29:37,242 --> 00:29:39,844
He begins to use MSG behind our backs.

771
00:29:39,911 --> 00:29:41,746
At this rate, he'll even
serve delivery food someday.

772
00:29:41,946 --> 00:29:43,047
SAMDASH

773
00:29:43,114 --> 00:29:45,383
Clams with MSG are guaranteed to be…

774
00:29:45,450 --> 00:29:46,885
It's an explosion of umami.

775
00:29:47,218 --> 00:29:48,720
HOW WILL POONG FIGHT HIS MSG?

776
00:29:49,287 --> 00:29:50,722
Kim Poong's famous chili oil.

777
00:29:50,789 --> 00:29:52,056
I knew it.

778
00:29:52,824 --> 00:29:53,725
SLAM

779
00:29:54,159 --> 00:29:55,460
GARLIC SMASHED BY HAND

780
00:29:55,527 --> 00:29:56,761
As always, Poong's chili oil.

781
00:29:56,828 --> 00:29:59,230
He never skips making chili oil.

782
00:29:59,297 --> 00:30:01,399
He's straining the oil into what?

783
00:30:01,466 --> 00:30:03,501
-It's perilla powder.
-Perilla powder.

784
00:30:03,568 --> 00:30:05,236
MIX WITH PERILLA POWDER

785
00:30:05,303 --> 00:30:06,571
It's a twist I'm adding.

786
00:30:06,638 --> 00:30:08,173
The nutty aroma will seep inside,

787
00:30:08,239 --> 00:30:11,176
so it'll taste delicious
with anything, including <i>bibim-dangmyeon.</i>

788
00:30:11,242 --> 00:30:14,179
-Is that basically the sauce?
-Yes.

789
00:30:14,245 --> 00:30:15,914
I'm adding some perilla aroma too.

790
00:30:15,980 --> 00:30:18,416
-I can smell it.
-Yes, it smells strong.

791
00:30:18,483 --> 00:30:22,187
I think he's making something
far from the order I asked for.

792
00:30:22,253 --> 00:30:24,122
Just be quiet.

793
00:30:24,189 --> 00:30:26,224
Just be grateful
that they're cooking for you.

794
00:30:26,291 --> 00:30:27,992
Where are your manners?

795
00:30:28,927 --> 00:30:30,862
I guess he's starting
with the hot pot rice.

796
00:30:31,095 --> 00:30:33,198
1. ADD SOAKED RICE AND WATER
INTO A STONE POT

797
00:30:33,264 --> 00:30:35,834
Is there a reason
why you're using more water than usual?

798
00:30:35,900 --> 00:30:38,269
I'm going to add these on top later.

799
00:30:38,336 --> 00:30:41,372
He's adding more water than usual
to top it with <i>dureup</i> later.

800
00:30:44,242 --> 00:30:46,311
Let's see how Poong uses his knife.

801
00:30:46,377 --> 00:30:48,580
We've already seen how Moon-jung chops.

802
00:30:48,646 --> 00:30:50,215
HER SMOOTH KNIFE SKILLS

803
00:30:51,182 --> 00:30:52,550
Poong's about to chop!

804
00:30:53,952 --> 00:30:54,853
Whoa.

805
00:30:54,919 --> 00:30:55,820
-Whoa.
-Whoa.

806
00:30:55,887 --> 00:30:57,188
Poong's about to chop!

807
00:30:57,255 --> 00:30:59,457
ROLLING AWAY

808
00:30:59,691 --> 00:31:01,593
LIKE ANCHOVIES THAT
JUMP OUT OF THE SEA BY BUSAN

809
00:31:01,926 --> 00:31:03,895
RADISH PIECES JUMP EVERYWHERE

810
00:31:03,962 --> 00:31:06,231
He chops and adds some radish
to create a refreshing flavor.

811
00:31:06,297 --> 00:31:07,932
First, the radish.

812
00:31:07,999 --> 00:31:09,801
-The eel.
-The eel.

813
00:31:09,868 --> 00:31:11,069
-The eel.
-He's starting now.

814
00:31:11,135 --> 00:31:12,770
-He's using the eel.
-Eel.

815
00:31:13,771 --> 00:31:15,406
-He can't cut it.
-That's how he's cutting it?

816
00:31:15,840 --> 00:31:17,342
WHAT THE HECK IS THAT?

817
00:31:17,408 --> 00:31:18,910
For <i>jangeo-tang…</i>

818
00:31:18,977 --> 00:31:20,411
Watch your hand.

819
00:31:20,478 --> 00:31:22,547
-Careful.
-It'll be slippery.

820
00:31:22,614 --> 00:31:24,282
It's slippery, so you may hurt your hand.

821
00:31:24,349 --> 00:31:26,017
FORCING IT WITH HIS POWER

822
00:31:26,084 --> 00:31:28,686
The pieces don't look too even,

823
00:31:28,753 --> 00:31:30,622
but it's for a stew, anyway.

824
00:31:30,688 --> 00:31:33,591
-The eel.
-He's adding <i>doenjang</i> into the soup.

825
00:31:33,658 --> 00:31:35,360
-Tuna sauce.
-Tuna sauce.

826
00:31:35,426 --> 00:31:36,928
Dongnae scallion <i>jeon</i>.

827
00:31:36,995 --> 00:31:38,096
He's starting on the <i>jeon</i>.

828
00:31:38,162 --> 00:31:40,999
-You need to use lots of scallions.
-Scallions. Yes.

829
00:31:41,065 --> 00:31:44,135
Manager Choi must be very familiar
with Dongnae scallion <i>jeon</i>.

830
00:31:44,202 --> 00:31:45,703
And you begin just with scallions?

831
00:31:45,770 --> 00:31:48,640
That <i>jeon</i> needs to be quite thick, right?

832
00:31:48,706 --> 00:31:50,241
Dongnae scallion <i>jeon </i>is thin.

833
00:31:50,308 --> 00:31:52,744
The balance between the batter

834
00:31:52,810 --> 00:31:55,847
-and scallions is everything.
-Balance is everything.

835
00:31:55,914 --> 00:31:58,416
Yes, I made a very thin batter

836
00:31:58,483 --> 00:32:00,652
by using just the sticky rice powder.

837
00:32:00,718 --> 00:32:02,387
It uses lots of scallions.

838
00:32:02,453 --> 00:32:04,489
It's different
from the scallion <i>jeon</i> in Seoul.

839
00:32:04,555 --> 00:32:06,457
It requires lots of scallions.

840
00:32:07,525 --> 00:32:08,626
Is that sea bass?

841
00:32:08,693 --> 00:32:10,795
-It is.
-That looks so plump.

842
00:32:10,862 --> 00:32:12,997
That's sea bass? That's huge.

843
00:32:13,064 --> 00:32:15,133
He wants his presence to be known.

844
00:32:15,199 --> 00:32:17,902
Make something
that'll remind him strongly of Busan.

845
00:32:17,969 --> 00:32:19,837
Napa cabbage.

846
00:32:20,805 --> 00:32:22,373
Napa cabbage. Must chop the cabbage.

847
00:32:22,440 --> 00:32:23,708
It'll make the dish refreshing.

848
00:32:23,775 --> 00:32:27,011
-It'll be refreshing. Chopping cabbage.
-He's chopping napa cabbage.

849
00:32:27,078 --> 00:32:28,112
It's for the stew.

850
00:32:28,179 --> 00:32:29,881
For <i>bibim-dangmyeon</i> too.

851
00:32:29,948 --> 00:32:33,251
-And <i>bibim-dangmyeon.</i>
-Both that and <i>jangeo-tang.</i>

852
00:32:33,318 --> 00:32:37,255
-Perilla leaves.
-Poong's prepping everything smoothly.

853
00:32:37,322 --> 00:32:38,489
-Is he?
-Yes.

854
00:32:38,556 --> 00:32:39,924
Chives.

855
00:32:39,991 --> 00:32:43,594
NEXT VEGGIE TO ADD THE BUSAN VIBE!

856
00:32:43,661 --> 00:32:46,230
He's using fish cake.
Busan is famous for its fish cake.

857
00:32:46,297 --> 00:32:48,633
Along with <i>bibim-dangmyeon,</i>
Busan is all about fish cake!

858
00:32:48,700 --> 00:32:50,535
-You can't leave it out.
-You can't.

859
00:32:50,601 --> 00:32:52,737
Busan is all about fish cake! Right?

860
00:32:53,271 --> 00:32:55,206
SCORING POINTS WITH FISH CAKE

861
00:32:55,540 --> 00:32:57,442
THE BUSAN GUY IS PLEASED

862
00:32:57,675 --> 00:33:01,045
FISH CAKE FOR BIBIM-DANGMYEON

863
00:33:01,112 --> 00:33:02,814
What about squid?

864
00:33:02,880 --> 00:33:03,982
Do you enjoy squid?

865
00:33:04,048 --> 00:33:05,416
-I do.
-You love them.

866
00:33:05,483 --> 00:33:06,651
Is that for the scallion <i>jeon?</i>

867
00:33:06,718 --> 00:33:08,519
-You're right.
-It's for the <i>jeon</i>.

868
00:33:08,586 --> 00:33:11,489
-It's a must for scallion <i>jeon</i>.
-You need it to add that bite.

869
00:33:11,556 --> 00:33:12,924
Yes.

870
00:33:12,991 --> 00:33:16,294
Dongnae scallion <i>jeon</i> is
coming along well. It smells amazing.

871
00:33:16,361 --> 00:33:18,463
He tops it with squid and shrimp.

872
00:33:18,529 --> 00:33:20,898
-He really loves <i>jeon</i>.
-He does?

873
00:33:20,965 --> 00:33:22,033
JEON IS THE BEST

874
00:33:22,934 --> 00:33:25,770
-He especially loves <i>jeon</i>.
-Call him <i>Jeon</i> Yong-soo.

875
00:33:27,538 --> 00:33:29,073
Your hot pot rice is overflowing.

876
00:33:29,140 --> 00:33:30,608
-The rice.
-The lid.

877
00:33:30,675 --> 00:33:33,344
-You should open the lid just once.
-The rice.

878
00:33:34,012 --> 00:33:35,313
LETTING THE STEAM OUT

879
00:33:35,380 --> 00:33:38,516
-He used too much water.
-You did add more water than usual.

880
00:33:38,583 --> 00:33:39,951
Manager Choi may like

881
00:33:40,018 --> 00:33:41,652
his rice a little mushier and softer.

882
00:33:42,687 --> 00:33:43,788
Not at all.

883
00:33:43,855 --> 00:33:45,823
-He doesn't like mushy rice.
-Not at all.

884
00:33:45,890 --> 00:33:47,558
-He doesn't like it.
-No mushy rice.

885
00:33:47,625 --> 00:33:48,893
Ten minutes remain.

886
00:33:48,960 --> 00:33:49,861
Already?

887
00:33:49,927 --> 00:33:52,864
-Time is flying.
-Time goes by very fast.

888
00:33:52,930 --> 00:33:56,200
-As we speak, he's using abalone.
-Abalone.

889
00:33:56,267 --> 00:33:57,235
Seafood.

890
00:33:57,301 --> 00:33:58,403
A HUGE FROWN

891
00:33:58,469 --> 00:34:02,106
-He's fighting against the abalones.
-It won't come off.

892
00:34:02,173 --> 00:34:04,942
-Come on!
-He's putting up a fight against abalones!

893
00:34:05,009 --> 00:34:06,978
One more. He's using three.

894
00:34:07,045 --> 00:34:09,614
-It'd be easier if you blanched it.
-It's done.

895
00:34:09,680 --> 00:34:11,182
Careful with the innards.

896
00:34:11,249 --> 00:34:13,017
That's how he chops abalones?

897
00:34:13,084 --> 00:34:14,986
It's too slippery to do that.

898
00:34:15,053 --> 00:34:16,587
If it's too hard, use scissors!

899
00:34:16,654 --> 00:34:18,656
Poong cuts off the innards.

900
00:34:19,524 --> 00:34:22,160
It's like they're on a mudflat.

901
00:34:22,226 --> 00:34:24,095
-They must be alive.
-They're running around.

902
00:34:24,162 --> 00:34:25,530
Just like that?

903
00:34:25,596 --> 00:34:27,432
He's boiling the abalones.

904
00:34:27,498 --> 00:34:30,701
-That and fish cake.
-Abalones and fish cake.

905
00:34:30,768 --> 00:34:32,403
CABBAGE & ABALONE & FISH CAKE, JANGEO-TANG

906
00:34:32,470 --> 00:34:34,605
-Poong, the instant rice.
-Warm up the rice.

907
00:34:34,672 --> 00:34:36,374
-The instant rice.
-The instant rice.

908
00:34:36,441 --> 00:34:37,642
The instant rice.

909
00:34:38,242 --> 00:34:39,510
Just warm it up.

910
00:34:39,811 --> 00:34:41,312
WHAT'S SAM UP TO?

911
00:34:41,612 --> 00:34:44,482
FLIP THE SEA BASS ON THE PAN

912
00:34:44,549 --> 00:34:47,685
Look at how plump it is.
Will all of its meat get cooked?

913
00:34:47,752 --> 00:34:49,020
-It'll take a while.
-It's so thick.

914
00:34:49,987 --> 00:34:51,556
TIME TO FLIP THE SCALLION JEON

915
00:34:51,622 --> 00:34:52,757
Dongnae scallion <i>jeon!</i>

916
00:34:52,824 --> 00:34:53,958
THE SCALLION JEON FLIES

917
00:34:54,725 --> 00:34:55,993
The <i>jeon!</i>

918
00:34:56,060 --> 00:34:58,229
A PERFECT STROLL AROUND DONGNAE

919
00:34:58,296 --> 00:35:00,932
-He did it.
-That was really good.

920
00:35:00,998 --> 00:35:05,336
-He drizzles more batter on top.
-So that's how you make it.

921
00:35:05,970 --> 00:35:07,105
SOY SAUCE

922
00:35:07,171 --> 00:35:08,239
RED PEPPER POWDER

923
00:35:08,573 --> 00:35:10,041
CRUSHED GARLIC

924
00:35:10,808 --> 00:35:12,477
The way he chops that pepper
hits different.

925
00:35:12,543 --> 00:35:13,845
-Different from Poong.
-Yes.

926
00:35:13,911 --> 00:35:16,247
I think he's making sauce.
What's that for?

927
00:35:16,314 --> 00:35:18,349
This? The hot pot rice.

928
00:35:18,416 --> 00:35:21,352
-It's for the hot pot rice.
-For you to eat with the rice.

929
00:35:21,419 --> 00:35:23,855
Six minutes remain.

930
00:35:23,921 --> 00:35:26,591
<i>Bibim-dangmyeon</i> sauce.

931
00:35:26,657 --> 00:35:30,461
He's using tomato sauce
to make <i>bibim-dangmyeon</i> sauce.

932
00:35:30,528 --> 00:35:32,797
-Tomato sauce?
-And chili oil.

933
00:35:32,864 --> 00:35:34,999
-It's hard to imagine.
-Oyster sauce.

934
00:35:35,066 --> 00:35:36,467
-Vinegar.
-What's that for?

935
00:35:36,534 --> 00:35:37,969
<i>-Bibim-dangmyeon.</i>
<i>-Bibim-dangmyeon.</i>

936
00:35:38,035 --> 00:35:39,637
<i>-Bibim-dangmyeon.</i>
-Yes.

937
00:35:39,704 --> 00:35:41,906
-You should cook the glass noodles.
-The noodles.

938
00:35:41,973 --> 00:35:43,508
The glass noodles?

939
00:35:43,574 --> 00:35:44,609
No, not yet.

940
00:35:44,675 --> 00:35:46,377
You only have five minutes left.

941
00:35:46,444 --> 00:35:48,279
He scoops the fish cake out,

942
00:35:48,346 --> 00:35:49,814
as well as the abalones.

943
00:35:49,881 --> 00:35:51,182
What are those for?

944
00:35:51,249 --> 00:35:52,316
Cook the glass noodles.

945
00:35:52,383 --> 00:35:53,985
Beef soup stock.

946
00:35:54,051 --> 00:35:55,419
-Beef soup stock?
-Glass noodles.

947
00:35:55,486 --> 00:35:57,288
-In there?
-You added a bit too much.

948
00:35:57,355 --> 00:35:58,322
-Tuna sauce.
-That's too much.

949
00:35:58,389 --> 00:35:59,590
-What's it for?
-Tuna sauce?

950
00:35:59,657 --> 00:36:02,360
-And oyster sauce? Try it.
-You should try it first.

951
00:36:02,426 --> 00:36:03,728
That'll taste way too strong.

952
00:36:03,794 --> 00:36:05,196
Not at all.

953
00:36:05,263 --> 00:36:07,298
He added three kinds of flavor enhancers.

954
00:36:07,365 --> 00:36:09,233
And in goes glass noodles.

955
00:36:09,300 --> 00:36:11,035
He seasoned that water first.

956
00:36:11,102 --> 00:36:13,037
It must be to let the flavor seep into it.

957
00:36:13,104 --> 00:36:14,172
Five minutes left.

958
00:36:14,238 --> 00:36:15,273
Five minutes left.

959
00:36:15,339 --> 00:36:17,975
Five minutes left, Sung-ju.
Can you report from the kitchen?

960
00:36:18,042 --> 00:36:20,278
I'm on my way. Hey!

961
00:36:20,344 --> 00:36:23,714
Five minutes left
as he flips Dongnae scallion <i>jeon</i> again.

962
00:36:23,781 --> 00:36:26,150
OH, MY, THAT LOOKS DELICIOUS

963
00:36:26,217 --> 00:36:28,286
He's making Dongnae scallion <i>jeon</i>.

964
00:36:28,352 --> 00:36:30,621
And he's cooking sea bass.

965
00:36:30,688 --> 00:36:31,989
This is sea bass soup, right?

966
00:36:32,223 --> 00:36:33,491
GRILLED SEA BASS

967
00:36:34,091 --> 00:36:36,561
He grilled it in a pan first.

968
00:36:36,627 --> 00:36:39,997
-And he's going to grill it once more.
-That looks good.

969
00:36:40,064 --> 00:36:42,333
Now, he's grilling sea bass over here.

970
00:36:42,400 --> 00:36:43,768
Are you going to grind that?

971
00:36:43,834 --> 00:36:47,038
I hope you get the stew right.
Is this it? The <i>jangeo-tang?</i>

972
00:36:47,104 --> 00:36:49,807
Wait a second.
He's putting the broth in here.

973
00:36:49,874 --> 00:36:51,642
-He'll blend it.
-He'll blend the mixture.

974
00:36:51,709 --> 00:36:54,212
I'll mix the blended mixture
with the rest of the stew.

975
00:36:54,278 --> 00:36:56,614
Bigger pieces with thicker soup, then.

976
00:36:56,681 --> 00:36:58,416
-That's a smart move.
-That looks good.

977
00:36:58,950 --> 00:37:00,418
-Let me try the soup.
-<i>Jangeo-tang.</i>

978
00:37:00,484 --> 00:37:02,086
Can he score a goal with that shot?

979
00:37:02,420 --> 00:37:03,888
CAN HE SCORE A GOAL?

980
00:37:03,955 --> 00:37:05,656
OR WILL HE GET FLOORED?

981
00:37:06,390 --> 00:37:08,326
Well, I can taste

982
00:37:08,392 --> 00:37:10,027
a bit of fishiness.

983
00:37:10,094 --> 00:37:12,396
-It tastes fishy?
-Is fishiness okay?

984
00:37:12,463 --> 00:37:14,532
-I don't really like it.
-He doesn't like it.

985
00:37:14,599 --> 00:37:17,034
The eel stew tastes a bit fishy.
Is that all right?

986
00:37:17,101 --> 00:37:20,071
-It still tastes a bit fishy.
-I'll get rid of it.

987
00:37:20,137 --> 00:37:22,773
-Perilla powder.
-He's using perilla powder to do that.

988
00:37:22,840 --> 00:37:24,809
And vinegar. It needs vinegar.

989
00:37:24,875 --> 00:37:26,544
<i>Jangeo-tang.</i>

990
00:37:26,611 --> 00:37:29,547
This is Poong's ambitious dish,
<i>jangeo-tang.</i>

991
00:37:30,181 --> 00:37:31,182
Three minutes.

992
00:37:31,249 --> 00:37:32,984
-Is the rice almost done?
-It's almost done.

993
00:37:33,050 --> 00:37:34,785
-It's almost done.
-<i>Dureup.</i>

994
00:37:34,852 --> 00:37:36,354
-<i>Dureup?</i>
-<i>Dureup.</i>

995
00:37:36,420 --> 00:37:40,091
-It goes on top of the hot pot rice.
-<i>Dureup </i>with rice.

996
00:37:40,157 --> 00:37:41,659
This is the clear soup, right?

997
00:37:41,726 --> 00:37:42,560
Yes, try it.

998
00:37:42,627 --> 00:37:45,496
-It's clear sea bass soup.
-Enjoy the refreshing taste.

999
00:37:45,563 --> 00:37:48,165
Will it make Busan seagulls soar?

1000
00:37:48,899 --> 00:37:49,967
Is your stew ready?

1001
00:37:50,034 --> 00:37:51,769
His <i>jangeo-tang</i> is important.

1002
00:37:51,836 --> 00:37:53,304
Did he get rid of the fishy smell?

1003
00:37:53,371 --> 00:37:54,572
So hot! Darn it, you punk!

1004
00:37:57,008 --> 00:37:58,242
Hey, Poong.

1005
00:37:58,309 --> 00:38:00,945
-Were you talking to me? Was it me?
-No.

1006
00:38:01,178 --> 00:38:03,247
LAUGHING OUT LOUD

1007
00:38:03,314 --> 00:38:04,649
-Should I not taste it?
-No, try it.

1008
00:38:04,715 --> 00:38:06,984
-No, you can try it.
-Can I?

1009
00:38:07,051 --> 00:38:08,085
I can try it, right?

1010
00:38:08,152 --> 00:38:10,354
I mean, you said, "You punk!"

1011
00:38:10,421 --> 00:38:12,089
Did he get rid of the fishy taste?

1012
00:38:12,323 --> 00:38:14,258
DID HE GET RID OF THE FISHINESS?

1013
00:38:14,558 --> 00:38:16,427
He did! The fishiness is gone!

1014
00:38:16,494 --> 00:38:19,530
He made it a little spicy
to get rid of that smell.

1015
00:38:19,597 --> 00:38:22,366
-You're right.
-Instead of making <i>jiri</i>, clear soup.

1016
00:38:22,433 --> 00:38:24,568
-What about abalones?
-<i>Bibim-dangmyeon!</i>

1017
00:38:24,635 --> 00:38:27,672
-The <i>bibim-dangmyeon</i> he mentioned.
-The abalones and all.

1018
00:38:27,738 --> 00:38:30,141
He's adding abalones and fish cake here.

1019
00:38:30,207 --> 00:38:31,142
It didn't go in.

1020
00:38:31,742 --> 00:38:34,478
-Why did you throw the abalone away?
-Where?

1021
00:38:34,545 --> 00:38:36,347
The abalone a-fell-one.

1022
00:38:36,414 --> 00:38:37,715
THE BIGGEST LAUGHTER

1023
00:38:38,949 --> 00:38:41,085
-A-fell-one.
-Let me try this one.

1024
00:38:41,152 --> 00:38:42,720
-Can I try it?
-You can.

1025
00:38:42,787 --> 00:38:45,122
How's the abalone a-fell-one?

1026
00:38:45,189 --> 00:38:46,824
It's delicious!

1027
00:38:46,891 --> 00:38:49,560
-It's really good.
-How's the texture?

1028
00:38:49,627 --> 00:38:50,928
It's great. He did a great job.

1029
00:38:50,995 --> 00:38:52,196
ANOTHER QUICK SWIRL OF SAUCE

1030
00:38:52,263 --> 00:38:54,131
-One minute left.
-One minute!

1031
00:38:54,465 --> 00:38:56,967
THE JEON GUY PLATES HIS FOOD!

1032
00:38:58,402 --> 00:38:59,804
CLEAR SEA BASS SOUP TOO!

1033
00:38:59,870 --> 00:39:02,106
You do not have much time.

1034
00:39:02,173 --> 00:39:03,974
LOTS OF SEAFOOD

1035
00:39:04,041 --> 00:39:06,344
-That sea bass looks good.
-It's nicely cooked.

1036
00:39:06,410 --> 00:39:08,612
You do not have much time.

1037
00:39:08,679 --> 00:39:09,680
Fifteen seconds.

1038
00:39:09,747 --> 00:39:11,549
COOKED CABBAGE AND CHIVES

1039
00:39:12,016 --> 00:39:13,184
PERILLA POWDER

1040
00:39:13,250 --> 00:39:14,785
-Ten. Nine.
-Instant rice!

1041
00:39:14,852 --> 00:39:16,020
-Instant rice!
-Eight.

1042
00:39:16,087 --> 00:39:17,555
-The rice.
-Seven.

1043
00:39:17,621 --> 00:39:19,390
-Rice.
-Six. Five.

1044
00:39:19,457 --> 00:39:22,360
-Turn it over.
-Four. Three. Two.

1045
00:39:22,426 --> 00:39:24,562
-Five. Four.
-Five. Four.

1046
00:39:24,628 --> 00:39:27,331
-Three. Two. One.
-Three. Two. One.

1047
00:39:27,398 --> 00:39:28,733
Sam finishes first.

1048
00:39:28,799 --> 00:39:31,402
Poong is also finished.

1049
00:39:31,469 --> 00:39:33,170
No one can make another dish now.

1050
00:39:33,237 --> 00:39:35,139
A Seafood Dish
to Make Busan Seagulls Soar.

1051
00:39:35,206 --> 00:39:36,340
TWO HEARTY BUSAN MEALS

1052
00:39:36,407 --> 00:39:38,909
-That's a feast.
-Look at that.

1053
00:39:39,610 --> 00:39:41,345
This is fascinating.

1054
00:39:41,412 --> 00:39:43,214
Thank you, both of you.

1055
00:39:43,481 --> 00:39:44,582
A BOW

1056
00:39:44,648 --> 00:39:48,586
All seafood dishes were finished
just for Manager Choi Yong-soo.

1057
00:39:48,786 --> 00:39:49,720
PLEASED

1058
00:39:50,721 --> 00:39:52,723
Are you pleased?

1059
00:39:52,790 --> 00:39:55,860
I'm more particular about food
than I seem.

1060
00:39:55,926 --> 00:39:56,894
I have a refined taste.

1061
00:39:56,961 --> 00:39:57,862
PFFT

1062
00:39:59,363 --> 00:40:01,365
Come on. Please.

1063
00:40:01,632 --> 00:40:03,701
IT'S ALWAYS FUNNY TO SEE THEM BICKER

1064
00:40:03,768 --> 00:40:05,703
-That's uncomfortable to hear.
-Right.

1065
00:40:05,770 --> 00:40:07,772
Also, what we're looking forward to

1066
00:40:07,838 --> 00:40:12,042
-is the reviews that ChoiPT prepared.
-His review.

1067
00:40:12,343 --> 00:40:14,378
TROUBLED

1068
00:40:14,445 --> 00:40:15,946
He saved them last week.

1069
00:40:16,013 --> 00:40:18,816
He already used one, though.
The analogy with Son Heung-min.

1070
00:40:18,883 --> 00:40:21,786
Now, please try Chef Sam's dishes first.

1071
00:40:21,852 --> 00:40:24,455
Want to Stroll Around Dongnae With Me?

1072
00:40:24,522 --> 00:40:25,890
DONGNAE SCALLION JEON

1073
00:40:25,956 --> 00:40:27,758
GRILLED SEA BASS

1074
00:40:27,825 --> 00:40:30,561
CLEAR SEA BASS SOUP

1075
00:40:30,628 --> 00:40:33,330
DUREUP HOT POT RICE

1076
00:40:34,632 --> 00:40:37,902
CHEF SAM KIM'S
WANT TO STROLL AROUND DONGNAE WITH ME?

1077
00:40:37,968 --> 00:40:41,172
That rice has <i>dureup</i> on top of it.

1078
00:40:41,238 --> 00:40:42,973
He said he doesn't like mushy rice.

1079
00:40:43,040 --> 00:40:44,175
The rice first.

1080
00:40:44,241 --> 00:40:46,210
UNCOVERING THE HOT POT RICE

1081
00:40:46,277 --> 00:40:47,411
It's on fire!

1082
00:40:47,478 --> 00:40:49,747
-Actually…
-Are you pleased?

1083
00:40:50,548 --> 00:40:52,983
I have yet to try it,

1084
00:40:53,050 --> 00:40:55,386
but it looks very delicious.

1085
00:40:55,453 --> 00:40:56,554
You look happy.

1086
00:40:57,521 --> 00:40:58,789
Mix it and scoop it into the bowl.

1087
00:40:58,856 --> 00:41:00,491
MIX AND LET DUREUP GIVE OFF ITS FLAVOR

1088
00:41:01,225 --> 00:41:04,261
-I think the rice was cooked perfectly.
-Was it?

1089
00:41:04,328 --> 00:41:06,664
At first, I was worried
it would turn out too mushy

1090
00:41:06,730 --> 00:41:09,433
-because he added too much water.
-I see.

1091
00:41:09,500 --> 00:41:12,002
-That's perfect.
-Were you?

1092
00:41:12,470 --> 00:41:13,304
SNIFF

1093
00:41:13,370 --> 00:41:15,739
-Did you add sesame oil?
-I did.

1094
00:41:15,806 --> 00:41:17,007
It looks good.

1095
00:41:17,074 --> 00:41:18,175
It smells really good.

1096
00:41:18,242 --> 00:41:19,910
You said you wouldn't use your dialect.

1097
00:41:19,977 --> 00:41:20,811
Sorry?

1098
00:41:20,878 --> 00:41:22,012
"Did you add sesame oil?"

1099
00:41:23,614 --> 00:41:25,616
Chef Hyun-suk,
I have lots of respect for you,

1100
00:41:25,683 --> 00:41:27,418
but we aren't on the same page today.

1101
00:41:27,485 --> 00:41:28,819
DISHEARTENED

1102
00:41:29,119 --> 00:41:31,222
A STRIKE IN A GENTLE TONE

1103
00:41:31,288 --> 00:41:32,256
I wonder.

1104
00:41:32,323 --> 00:41:33,924
DIPPED INTO CHOGOCHUJANG

1105
00:41:33,991 --> 00:41:35,993
TRYING THE DUREUP FIRST

1106
00:41:36,193 --> 00:41:37,228
It must be good.

1107
00:41:38,095 --> 00:41:39,597
WHAT'S IT LIKE?

1108
00:41:40,898 --> 00:41:42,366
A SMILE

1109
00:41:42,633 --> 00:41:43,634
HE CAN'T HIDE HIS SMILE

1110
00:41:43,701 --> 00:41:44,735
He looks so happy.

1111
00:41:44,802 --> 00:41:46,337
His face instantly changed.

1112
00:41:46,403 --> 00:41:47,805
It's my first time

1113
00:41:47,872 --> 00:41:50,241
eating stone pot rice with <i>dureup</i>.

1114
00:41:50,307 --> 00:41:54,211
-It's different from the blanched ones.
-I see.

1115
00:41:54,278 --> 00:41:55,312
One more.

1116
00:41:56,213 --> 00:41:57,348
This time, with the rice.

1117
00:41:57,414 --> 00:41:58,516
With the rice.

1118
00:42:00,784 --> 00:42:02,620
A BIG BITE

1119
00:42:03,654 --> 00:42:04,488
HOT

1120
00:42:05,823 --> 00:42:06,657
HOT

1121
00:42:06,724 --> 00:42:07,658
It's still hot.

1122
00:42:07,858 --> 00:42:09,660
IT'S SO HOT

1123
00:42:09,727 --> 00:42:11,896
-It must be hot. It's hot.
-It's too hot.

1124
00:42:11,962 --> 00:42:13,364
I HAVE MY EYES ON YOU

1125
00:42:13,764 --> 00:42:15,933
I MUST RISE ABOVE THIS

1126
00:42:16,166 --> 00:42:17,701
SUDDENLY YELLING AT THE HOT POT RICE

1127
00:42:17,768 --> 00:42:19,570
We're hearing him roar.

1128
00:42:19,637 --> 00:42:22,940
-It's an emergency.
-When I had it with rice,

1129
00:42:23,007 --> 00:42:25,676
it's delicious in yet another way.

1130
00:42:25,743 --> 00:42:28,646
I tried so hard
not to use the word "delicious."

1131
00:42:28,712 --> 00:42:30,781
But I can't hold it back. It's great.

1132
00:42:30,848 --> 00:42:32,917
-It must be.
-Try it with the grilled fish.

1133
00:42:32,983 --> 00:42:34,685
-The fish?
-On top of the rice.

1134
00:42:34,752 --> 00:42:36,987
Put a piece of fish meat on the rice

1135
00:42:37,054 --> 00:42:40,257
-and have it with soy sauce and <i>dureup</i>.
-That's so plump.

1136
00:42:40,324 --> 00:42:42,826
-Sea basses are that huge.
-They are.

1137
00:42:42,893 --> 00:42:44,528
Look how thick it is.

1138
00:42:44,595 --> 00:42:46,230
DIPPED IN THE SOY-BASED SAUCE

1139
00:42:46,530 --> 00:42:48,532
TRIES JUST THE FISH MEAT FIRST

1140
00:42:48,732 --> 00:42:50,100
NERVOUS

1141
00:42:50,167 --> 00:42:53,103
Sea basses are rather bland, you know.

1142
00:42:53,170 --> 00:42:54,271
-They are.
-Yes.

1143
00:42:54,338 --> 00:42:56,440
But with this soy sauce,

1144
00:42:56,507 --> 00:43:00,644
it feels a bit more like
I'm by the sea in Busan.

1145
00:43:01,612 --> 00:43:02,980
He told you to try it with rice.

1146
00:43:03,280 --> 00:43:05,449
RICE WITH SEA BASS DIPPED IN SOY SAUCE

1147
00:43:06,016 --> 00:43:06,984
TAKES A HUGE BITE

1148
00:43:07,051 --> 00:43:09,253
He eats a huge amount of rice.

1149
00:43:09,320 --> 00:43:12,856
-And then, try the <i>jiri</i>.
-He must eat a lot.

1150
00:43:12,923 --> 00:43:15,593
And now, the clear sea bass soup.

1151
00:43:15,659 --> 00:43:18,596
The grilled sea bass

1152
00:43:18,662 --> 00:43:22,266
-was cooked perfectly.
-Is that so? It was grilled nicely.

1153
00:43:22,333 --> 00:43:24,234
I can almost hear

1154
00:43:24,301 --> 00:43:27,071
the sound of the waves
at the tip of my tongue.

1155
00:43:29,306 --> 00:43:31,408
I rather like how this feels.

1156
00:43:31,475 --> 00:43:34,278
-Was that by ChoiPT?
-What?

1157
00:43:34,878 --> 00:43:37,915
WOW… YOU HIT THE NAIL ON THE HEAD

1158
00:43:37,982 --> 00:43:40,050
What do you mean
by hearing the waves on your tongue?

1159
00:43:40,117 --> 00:43:42,553
I mean that the aroma from the sea

1160
00:43:42,620 --> 00:43:44,755
seems to jump around in my mouth.

1161
00:43:44,989 --> 00:43:46,090
TRYING NOT TO LAUGH

1162
00:43:46,724 --> 00:43:47,758
GLARING

1163
00:43:48,325 --> 00:43:49,593
LOL

1164
00:43:50,194 --> 00:43:52,096
A SIP OF THE CLEAR SEA BASS SOUP!

1165
00:43:53,797 --> 00:43:55,532
SAVORING

1166
00:43:56,333 --> 00:43:57,468
-Hey.
-"Hey"?

1167
00:43:57,735 --> 00:43:59,570
HEY-HO

1168
00:43:59,637 --> 00:44:02,272
-This is nice.
-It is?

1169
00:44:02,339 --> 00:44:05,542
I actually prefer <i>jiri</i>,
these clear fish soups,

1170
00:44:05,609 --> 00:44:08,646
compared to <i>maeun-tang, </i>which is spicy.

1171
00:44:08,712 --> 00:44:10,114
He didn't have much time,

1172
00:44:10,180 --> 00:44:14,284
but I can still taste
that deep flavor in the soup.

1173
00:44:15,886 --> 00:44:17,121
He's enjoying it.

1174
00:44:17,187 --> 00:44:18,489
-Ah.
-He likes it.

1175
00:44:19,189 --> 00:44:20,357
FINDS A WHOLE GARLIC CLOVE

1176
00:44:20,424 --> 00:44:21,825
How many garlic cloves did you use?

1177
00:44:21,892 --> 00:44:24,361
THE FIRST GUEST EVER TO ASK FOR
THE NUMBER OF GARLIC CLOVES USED

1178
00:44:24,428 --> 00:44:26,163
-About five to six.
-Six?

1179
00:44:26,230 --> 00:44:27,698
-Five?
-Yes.

1180
00:44:28,265 --> 00:44:30,334
Next time, please use ten.

1181
00:44:30,401 --> 00:44:32,503
He needs more garlic.

1182
00:44:33,070 --> 00:44:35,873
Did you intentionally cut
the chili pepper like this?

1183
00:44:35,939 --> 00:44:39,443
-I wanted to make the soup spicier.
-For the spiciness.

1184
00:44:39,510 --> 00:44:41,845
-You didn't take a bite, right?
-No.

1185
00:44:41,912 --> 00:44:44,848
You might take it the wrong way
when you get this at a restaurant.

1186
00:44:44,915 --> 00:44:46,950
That was exactly why I asked.

1187
00:44:47,017 --> 00:44:48,719
I'd be mistaken
if I saw this at a restaurant.

1188
00:44:48,786 --> 00:44:50,421
Was this really meant for me?

1189
00:44:51,722 --> 00:44:53,624
The one in the <i>jeon</i> is in tiny pieces.

1190
00:44:53,691 --> 00:44:56,093
-Right?
-Yes, the shapes were intentional.

1191
00:44:56,160 --> 00:44:57,027
Man.

1192
00:44:58,195 --> 00:44:59,363
The chili pepper is too spicy.

1193
00:44:59,563 --> 00:45:00,898
I TOLD YOU IT WAS FOR THE SOUP

1194
00:45:01,231 --> 00:45:02,266
WAVING HIS HAND

1195
00:45:02,332 --> 00:45:03,467
THUD

1196
00:45:03,534 --> 00:45:05,669
-It must be spicy.
-Oh, no.

1197
00:45:05,736 --> 00:45:09,139
It was for the soup's flavor,
so you shouldn't have had it.

1198
00:45:09,206 --> 00:45:11,542
The Busan seagull is having a rough time.

1199
00:45:11,608 --> 00:45:12,576
The seagull is on fire.

1200
00:45:12,643 --> 00:45:14,445
Onto the scallion <i>jeon</i>, then.

1201
00:45:14,511 --> 00:45:16,413
You should have it with <i>chogochujang</i>.

1202
00:45:16,480 --> 00:45:17,681
With <i>chogochujang?</i>

1203
00:45:17,748 --> 00:45:18,949
-There?
-With <i>chogochujang?</i>

1204
00:45:19,016 --> 00:45:21,652
-Dongnae scallion <i>jeon </i>is good with that.
-Really?

1205
00:45:21,719 --> 00:45:23,087
No, wait.

1206
00:45:23,153 --> 00:45:25,222
-It's served with soy sauce.
-Soy sauce.

1207
00:45:25,289 --> 00:45:26,724
You served it with soy sauce too.

1208
00:45:26,790 --> 00:45:28,225
Yes, there's soy sauce too.

1209
00:45:28,292 --> 00:45:31,462
-It could be different.
-He dips it in the soy sauce.

1210
00:45:32,296 --> 00:45:33,630
YUM

1211
00:45:34,098 --> 00:45:36,133
DID HE RECREATE
DONGNAE SCALLION JEON SUCCESSFULLY?

1212
00:45:36,200 --> 00:45:38,302
-Are you reminded of Dongnae?
-Dongnae scallion <i>jeon</i>.

1213
00:45:39,136 --> 00:45:41,271
DID THE BUSAN SEAGULL REMEMBER SOMETHING?

1214
00:45:41,338 --> 00:45:43,540
-He's about to say something.
-Here we go.

1215
00:45:43,607 --> 00:45:44,975
In my mouth…

1216
00:45:45,242 --> 00:45:46,877
SO INVESTED

1217
00:45:46,944 --> 00:45:50,380
I suddenly remembered
the memories from my childhood,

1218
00:45:50,447 --> 00:45:53,150
when I used to go to school in Busan.

1219
00:45:53,217 --> 00:45:55,152
SUMMONING MEMORIES
WITH DONGNAE SCALLION JEON

1220
00:45:55,219 --> 00:45:57,154
That's a ChoiPT line.

1221
00:45:57,221 --> 00:45:58,622
-It's not.
-It's not?

1222
00:45:58,689 --> 00:46:02,726
-But you did a great job with it.
-He made a tasty <i>jeon</i>.

1223
00:46:02,793 --> 00:46:05,329
Why don't you try it with <i>chogochujang?</i>

1224
00:46:05,395 --> 00:46:06,296
DIPPING IN CHOGOCHUJANG TOO

1225
00:46:06,363 --> 00:46:07,865
You might remember

1226
00:46:07,931 --> 00:46:09,633
that you also had it with <i>chogochujang.</i>

1227
00:46:09,700 --> 00:46:12,836
-What's it like with <i>chogochujang?</i>
<i>-Chogochujang?</i>

1228
00:46:12,903 --> 00:46:14,004
WHAT'S THE NEW MIX LIKE?

1229
00:46:14,071 --> 00:46:15,405
Do you remember something?

1230
00:46:16,173 --> 00:46:17,474
They don't go well together.

1231
00:46:17,808 --> 00:46:19,610
HE KNOWS WHAT HE LIKES

1232
00:46:19,676 --> 00:46:21,178
-A no is a no.
-Scallion <i>jeon</i>

1233
00:46:21,245 --> 00:46:23,113
-is simply best…
-With soy sauce?

1234
00:46:23,180 --> 00:46:25,616
-…with soy sauce.
-Let him eat it with soy sauce.

1235
00:46:25,682 --> 00:46:26,984
He's really honest.

1236
00:46:27,050 --> 00:46:28,552
It would be great

1237
00:46:29,153 --> 00:46:30,387
if I had some <i>makgeolli</i> with this.

1238
00:46:31,155 --> 00:46:32,256
-That'd be perfect.
-<i>Makgeolli</i>.

1239
00:46:32,322 --> 00:46:34,491
<i>Makgeolli</i> would've been perfect.

1240
00:46:34,558 --> 00:46:35,959
Didn't you get it ready?

1241
00:46:36,593 --> 00:46:37,628
Suddenly?

1242
00:46:37,694 --> 00:46:40,964
I saw you last time
serving champagne and everything here.

1243
00:46:41,031 --> 00:46:42,766
He watched the show.

1244
00:46:42,833 --> 00:46:44,768
I saw the guests drinking soju too.

1245
00:46:44,835 --> 00:46:47,237
-You served soju and everything.
-It's not that.

1246
00:46:47,304 --> 00:46:49,139
-Only if you have it in your fridge.
-In your fridge.

1247
00:46:49,206 --> 00:46:51,542
-He can't bring what you don't have.
-You don't have it.

1248
00:46:51,608 --> 00:46:54,411
If you had it in the fridge,
he would've pulled it out already.

1249
00:46:54,478 --> 00:46:56,747
-Should I look for it?
-Don't be too harsh on him.

1250
00:46:56,814 --> 00:46:57,714
Should I?

1251
00:46:57,781 --> 00:47:00,417
He's 50 years old now.

1252
00:47:00,484 --> 00:47:03,554
He's become too sensitive
after many years in show business.

1253
00:47:03,620 --> 00:47:05,722
Should I look for it? I will.

1254
00:47:05,789 --> 00:47:07,991
Man. I can't deal with this.
I'll look for it.

1255
00:47:08,058 --> 00:47:09,827
Check and see if he has <i>makgeolli</i>.

1256
00:47:09,893 --> 00:47:12,229
-I hope he does.
-The glass noodles are getting soggy.

1257
00:47:12,296 --> 00:47:14,665
-My glass noodles.
-Yes, right.

1258
00:47:14,731 --> 00:47:16,366
-No <i>makgeolli</i>.
-The noodles are getting soggy.

1259
00:47:16,433 --> 00:47:18,101
Stop looking. He doesn't have it.

1260
00:47:18,168 --> 00:47:19,736
I don't think he has it.

1261
00:47:19,803 --> 00:47:23,340
-I'm very happy with everything.
-He's happy with it.

1262
00:47:23,407 --> 00:47:27,578
Next, Webtoon Artist Poong's dishes.
Shooting for Wacky <i>Jangeo-tang.</i>

1263
00:47:28,145 --> 00:47:30,714
A BUSAN SPECIALTY SET MEAL
TO CAPTURE HIS TASTE

1264
00:47:31,648 --> 00:47:33,984
THICK JANGEO-TANG

1265
00:47:34,918 --> 00:47:37,521
AND SWEET AND SPICY BIBIM-DANGMYEON

1266
00:47:38,589 --> 00:47:41,925
WEBTOON ARTIST KIM POONG'S
SHOOTING FOR WACKY JANGEO-TANG

1267
00:47:42,593 --> 00:47:43,894
First, the <i>bibim-dangmyeon</i>.

1268
00:47:43,961 --> 00:47:44,928
I wonder what it's like.

1269
00:47:44,995 --> 00:47:47,598
He used abalone,
water parsley, napa cabbage,

1270
00:47:47,664 --> 00:47:49,666
-And fish cake.
-…and even fish cake.

1271
00:47:50,667 --> 00:47:52,269
It did get a bit soggy.

1272
00:47:52,336 --> 00:47:55,105
I like my noodles a bit soggy.

1273
00:47:55,172 --> 00:47:56,373
A HEARTWARMING MOMENT

1274
00:47:56,440 --> 00:47:58,275
He'll take it into consideration.

1275
00:47:58,342 --> 00:48:00,677
When you had soggy <i>bibim-myeon</i> with me,
didn't you tell me

1276
00:48:00,744 --> 00:48:02,212
to go and get a new one?

1277
00:48:03,480 --> 00:48:04,581
Let's see.

1278
00:48:04,648 --> 00:48:05,616
I think I remember that.

1279
00:48:05,849 --> 00:48:07,517
ADMITS IMMEDIATELY

1280
00:48:07,584 --> 00:48:09,720
THIS ISN'T THE RESPONSE I WANTED

1281
00:48:09,786 --> 00:48:13,891
Your senior athlete
is trying to give his review.

1282
00:48:13,957 --> 00:48:14,825
SLURP

1283
00:48:16,660 --> 00:48:17,527
He's slurping.

1284
00:48:18,962 --> 00:48:20,464
It's something people in Busan like,

1285
00:48:20,530 --> 00:48:22,499
but it's Manager Choi's first time
trying it.

1286
00:48:22,566 --> 00:48:24,668
-We often eat <i>milmyeon</i> in Gyeongsang-do.
-Right.

1287
00:48:24,735 --> 00:48:27,704
<i>Milmyeon, bibim-naengmyeon,</i>
and <i>bibim-guksu</i>

1288
00:48:27,771 --> 00:48:29,273
are all spicy, right?

1289
00:48:29,339 --> 00:48:32,576
But this is on the sweeter side, actually.

1290
00:48:32,643 --> 00:48:36,747
The redness of the sauce
is tomato sauce and chili oil.

1291
00:48:36,813 --> 00:48:38,548
-It's not too spicy.
-This one is

1292
00:48:38,615 --> 00:48:40,684
not too bad.

1293
00:48:40,751 --> 00:48:43,887
The water parsley and cabbage

1294
00:48:43,954 --> 00:48:46,456
add nice aromas to the dish.

1295
00:48:46,523 --> 00:48:48,091
I really love water parsley, <i>minari</i>.

1296
00:48:48,158 --> 00:48:49,626
You do.

1297
00:48:50,193 --> 00:48:51,762
And my go-to karaoke song is "Binari."

1298
00:48:53,163 --> 00:48:54,097
That wasn't funny.

1299
00:48:55,365 --> 00:48:56,700
EMBARRASSED…

1300
00:48:57,267 --> 00:48:58,602
WITH A HANDFUL OF WATER PARSLEY

1301
00:48:59,970 --> 00:49:01,505
Is there a song called "Minari"?

1302
00:49:01,571 --> 00:49:03,640
-He said "Binari."
-"Binari."

1303
00:49:05,542 --> 00:49:07,010
Even the younger generation

1304
00:49:07,077 --> 00:49:09,179
would love this kind of flavor.

1305
00:49:09,246 --> 00:49:10,914
Not only is it sweet,

1306
00:49:10,981 --> 00:49:13,183
but the noodles also have
a nice chew to it.

1307
00:49:13,250 --> 00:49:14,718
-It looks good.
-It looks good.

1308
00:49:14,785 --> 00:49:16,353
-How about the <i>jangeo-tang?</i>
<i>-Jangeo-tang?</i>

1309
00:49:16,420 --> 00:49:19,189
It's not easy
to make <i>jangeo-tang</i> taste good.

1310
00:49:19,256 --> 00:49:21,058
ON TOP OF THAT…

1311
00:49:21,124 --> 00:49:24,528
Also, I didn't see you use
Korean mint or prickly ash powder.

1312
00:49:24,594 --> 00:49:27,497
You didn't have any. If you did…

1313
00:49:28,065 --> 00:49:29,266
I didn't?

1314
00:49:29,333 --> 00:49:30,334
Your neighbor did.

1315
00:49:30,400 --> 00:49:32,402
-Should I look for them?
-No.

1316
00:49:34,104 --> 00:49:36,039
If he says, "I probably have it,"
then I must look.

1317
00:49:36,106 --> 00:49:38,809
It doesn't matter if it's there.
I need to start looking, period.

1318
00:49:38,875 --> 00:49:40,510
"Jung-hwan, I probably have it."

1319
00:49:40,577 --> 00:49:42,379
<i>-Jangeo-tang.</i>
<i>-Jangeo-tang.</i>

1320
00:49:42,446 --> 00:49:45,315
He blended some of the eel with soup,
but also left some big pieces in.

1321
00:49:45,382 --> 00:49:47,684
He's someone who loves <i>jangeo-tang.</i>

1322
00:49:47,751 --> 00:49:50,220
-He loves eels.
-I see.

1323
00:49:50,487 --> 00:49:52,222
CURIOUS

1324
00:49:52,289 --> 00:49:55,192
It really suits him
to eat it out of that earthen pot.

1325
00:49:55,258 --> 00:49:57,694
-Did he nail it?
-The eel

1326
00:49:57,761 --> 00:50:00,964
was cooked perfectly.

1327
00:50:01,031 --> 00:50:03,400
It melted like cotton candy.

1328
00:50:03,467 --> 00:50:04,668
Cotton candy.

1329
00:50:04,735 --> 00:50:06,269
-Was that ChoiPT?
-Cotton candy.

1330
00:50:06,336 --> 00:50:07,504
CAUGHT RED-HANDED

1331
00:50:07,571 --> 00:50:09,139
It feels like cotton candy.

1332
00:50:09,206 --> 00:50:10,073
Eel and cotton candy?

1333
00:50:10,140 --> 00:50:14,845
When eels are overcooked,
they start to break down,

1334
00:50:14,911 --> 00:50:16,279
but this is nice.

1335
00:50:16,346 --> 00:50:18,648
I added a bit of vinegar to prevent that.

1336
00:50:18,715 --> 00:50:22,753
It can help the eel maintain its texture.

1337
00:50:23,987 --> 00:50:27,424
Why did you use napa cabbage?

1338
00:50:27,491 --> 00:50:31,094
The original recipe
calls for dried radish greens.

1339
00:50:31,161 --> 00:50:34,264
-That's it.
-But you didn't have any,

1340
00:50:34,331 --> 00:50:36,800
so I used napa cabbage instead.

1341
00:50:36,867 --> 00:50:39,403
My fridge is missing too many ingredients.

1342
00:50:39,469 --> 00:50:40,837
I'm sorry.

1343
00:50:41,138 --> 00:50:42,806
REMINDED HIM OF HIS LACK OF PRESTIGE…

1344
00:50:42,873 --> 00:50:45,175
He could've had them eight years ago.

1345
00:50:45,242 --> 00:50:48,011
But the household's focus
has shifted toward their children.

1346
00:50:48,078 --> 00:50:51,014
Unfortunately, he had to substitute
the ingredient with napa cabbage.

1347
00:50:51,081 --> 00:50:55,052
By any chance, do you have
any other soccer-related reviews?

1348
00:50:56,053 --> 00:50:57,888
-There is one.
-You have one?

1349
00:50:57,954 --> 00:50:59,456
But it doesn't suit this dish.

1350
00:50:59,689 --> 00:51:01,558
UNABLE TO RUN

1351
00:51:01,825 --> 00:51:03,593
THE CHARMINGLY HONEST BUSAN SEAGULL

1352
00:51:03,660 --> 00:51:05,028
Maybe in the next round.

1353
00:51:05,095 --> 00:51:07,431
Well, he doesn't use them blindly.

1354
00:51:07,798 --> 00:51:09,699
LOOKING FOR THE BEST CHANCE

1355
00:51:09,766 --> 00:51:12,202
You could've mentioned
Lee Kang-in by now, but you didn't.

1356
00:51:12,269 --> 00:51:16,006
His chatbot gave him something
with Lee Kang-in, actually.

1357
00:51:16,073 --> 00:51:18,975
-I see.
-But I guess it's not for this one.

1358
00:51:19,042 --> 00:51:20,610
We'll have to move on.

1359
00:51:20,677 --> 00:51:24,114
-Manager Park, why don't you try some?
-Let's do that.

1360
00:51:24,181 --> 00:51:26,083
Want to Stroll Around Dongnae With Me?

1361
00:51:26,149 --> 00:51:28,151
This <i>jiri </i>is so refreshing.

1362
00:51:28,385 --> 00:51:29,986
CHUGGING THE CLEAR SOUP

1363
00:51:30,053 --> 00:51:31,021
-Nice.
-Mmm.

1364
00:51:31,855 --> 00:51:34,157
HANG-SEO GOES FOR THE GRILLED SEA BASS

1365
00:51:35,459 --> 00:51:38,595
Hang-seo looks quite pleased too.

1366
00:51:38,662 --> 00:51:40,330
That was such a hearty meal.

1367
00:51:42,532 --> 00:51:45,001
I actually prefer
spicy fish soup than clear ones,

1368
00:51:45,068 --> 00:51:47,938
-but this one was delicious.
-Wasn't it?

1369
00:51:48,004 --> 00:51:49,239
This <i>jiri</i>

1370
00:51:49,306 --> 00:51:54,044
just swaddled my tired brain tightly,

1371
00:51:54,111 --> 00:51:58,148
then woke me up with the spicy pepper,
like it's saying, "It's not over!"

1372
00:51:58,415 --> 00:51:59,850
PERFECT

1373
00:51:59,916 --> 00:52:01,017
That was a perfect review.

1374
00:52:01,084 --> 00:52:02,586
Did she use the chatbot?

1375
00:52:02,652 --> 00:52:04,955
Everyone enjoyed that.

1376
00:52:05,021 --> 00:52:07,657
Next, Webtoon Artist Poong's dish.

1377
00:52:07,724 --> 00:52:10,727
-Shooting for Wacky <i>Jangeo-tang.</i>
<i>-</i>Shooting for Wacky <i>Jangeo-tang.</i>

1378
00:52:10,794 --> 00:52:11,661
<i>Bibim-dangmyeon.</i>

1379
00:52:12,262 --> 00:52:13,430
MMM!

1380
00:52:13,964 --> 00:52:16,700
SAM HAS A SIP OF THE JANGEO-TANG

1381
00:52:18,034 --> 00:52:20,470
It's like <i>jjigae</i>.
It reminds me of soft tofu stew.

1382
00:52:20,537 --> 00:52:23,173
-It's like <i>sundubu-jjigae</i>.
-Yes.

1383
00:52:23,240 --> 00:52:24,508
It's so good.

1384
00:52:25,242 --> 00:52:27,344
HANG-SEO HAS A SPOONFUL OF JANGEO-TANG TOO

1385
00:52:28,578 --> 00:52:30,247
I like this thick stew.

1386
00:52:30,313 --> 00:52:32,349
There's a bit of sourness,

1387
00:52:32,415 --> 00:52:34,784
so even without kimchi,

1388
00:52:34,851 --> 00:52:38,722
it has that refreshing flavor
of something made with kimchi.

1389
00:52:38,788 --> 00:52:41,892
In Gyeongsang-do, we eat <i>milmyeon </i>often.

1390
00:52:41,958 --> 00:52:45,996
But I'm starting to feel
that this is better than <i>milmyeon,</i>

1391
00:52:46,062 --> 00:52:48,031
even though I had that more often.

1392
00:52:48,098 --> 00:52:50,200
And the stew.

1393
00:52:50,267 --> 00:52:52,769
I'm someone
who loves <i>chueo-tang</i>, loach soup,

1394
00:52:52,836 --> 00:52:54,137
Is it because he blended some of this?

1395
00:52:54,204 --> 00:52:58,441
-It has that <i>chueo-tang</i> texture.
-Yes, it's like <i>chueo-tang.</i>

1396
00:52:58,508 --> 00:53:00,010
It's now time to decide.

1397
00:53:00,076 --> 00:53:02,746
Manager Choi, you'll put a star
on one of the two.

1398
00:53:02,812 --> 00:53:04,414
<i>Press one to pick Sam Kim,</i>

1399
00:53:04,481 --> 00:53:05,749
<i>and two to pick Kim Poong.</i>

1400
00:53:06,349 --> 00:53:07,951
Please press a button.

1401
00:53:08,685 --> 00:53:11,087
HIS FINGER WANDERS…

1402
00:53:13,623 --> 00:53:14,891
-Did you press one?
-Yes.

1403
00:53:14,958 --> 00:53:16,660
-He's quick.
-That was quick.

1404
00:53:16,726 --> 00:53:19,196
Let's find out the result. Show us!

1405
00:53:20,130 --> 00:53:23,667
Manager Choi Yong-soo
wanted to eat a seafood dish.

1406
00:53:23,733 --> 00:53:25,368
Kim Poong versus Sam Kim.

1407
00:53:25,435 --> 00:53:28,605
They both have six stars as of now,

1408
00:53:28,672 --> 00:53:30,407
chasing right after Jong-won.

1409
00:53:30,473 --> 00:53:33,143
We're about to see
who'll become the sole second place.

1410
00:53:33,210 --> 00:53:36,346
Who's going to take the seventh star?

1411
00:53:36,413 --> 00:53:37,681
Who did Manager Choi choose?

1412
00:53:38,215 --> 00:53:41,051
Is it Poong or Sam?

1413
00:53:41,117 --> 00:53:44,087
Was it eel or sea bass?

1414
00:53:45,655 --> 00:53:46,990
KIM POONG WINS

1415
00:53:47,057 --> 00:53:48,391
Kim Poong wins!

1416
00:53:48,625 --> 00:53:50,860
SHOOTING FOR WACKY JANGEO-TANG WINS

1417
00:53:50,927 --> 00:53:52,529
Kim Poong wins!

1418
00:53:52,596 --> 00:53:53,730
EEL BEATS SEA BASS

1419
00:53:54,898 --> 00:53:57,968
Both the eel stew and the sea bass soup

1420
00:53:58,034 --> 00:53:59,836
were very nice.

1421
00:53:59,903 --> 00:54:01,705
But when it came to new ideas,

1422
00:54:01,771 --> 00:54:05,108
I found his <i>bibim-dangmyeon</i> enticing.

1423
00:54:05,175 --> 00:54:08,878
It's quite an addictive dish.

1424
00:54:08,945 --> 00:54:11,648
-And the Dongnae scallion <i>jeon </i>was great.
-It really was.

1425
00:54:11,715 --> 00:54:15,885
It did bring back my old memories.

1426
00:54:15,952 --> 00:54:17,687
-I'm sorry…
-No problem.

1427
00:54:17,754 --> 00:54:19,289
…and thank you for the hard work.

1428
00:54:19,356 --> 00:54:22,225
The legend of Poongphobia continues.

1429
00:54:22,926 --> 00:54:25,028
That's unfortunate, Sam.

1430
00:54:25,095 --> 00:54:27,897
-Sparkle, sparkle.
-Poong now gets his seventh star.

1431
00:54:27,964 --> 00:54:31,868
He now beats Sam
and rises as the sole second place.

1432
00:54:32,535 --> 00:54:33,670
Congratulations!

1433
00:54:35,305 --> 00:54:37,073
Great job, Poong.

1434
00:54:37,140 --> 00:54:41,511
<i>The second round of cook-off with</i>
<i>ingredients from Manager Choi's fridge.</i>

1435
00:54:41,578 --> 00:54:44,948
The two chefs who'll raise the prestige
of CEO Choi of House Ent.,

1436
00:54:45,015 --> 00:54:48,084
Chef Choi Hyun-suk
of Showoff Entertainment

1437
00:54:48,151 --> 00:54:51,788
and Chef Jung Ho-young
of Dancing Entertainment.

1438
00:54:51,855 --> 00:54:53,056
Apparently,

1439
00:54:53,123 --> 00:54:55,392
Chef Ho-young said

1440
00:54:55,458 --> 00:54:58,395
he was concerned about Hyun-suk
in this round.

1441
00:54:58,461 --> 00:55:00,030
-Why?
-Recently,

1442
00:55:00,096 --> 00:55:02,132
he keeps making mistakes when he cooks,

1443
00:55:02,198 --> 00:55:04,768
-and maybe it's due to his age.
-That's true. It's happened.

